# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-protection-party-of-canada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The **2006 Canadian federal election** was held on January 23, 2006, to elect members to the House of Commons of Canada of the 39th Parliament of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] New details of the sponsorship scandal were released through the Gomery Commission, and the three opposition parties aimed to bring down Liberal Prime Minister Paul Martin's minority government, contending that it was corrupt.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] On November 28, 2005, Martin's government was defeated on a motion of non-confidence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] A day later, Martin met with Governor General Michaëlle Jean to dissolve parliament, triggering an unusual winter election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservative Party, that was formed in 2003 from the merger of the Progressive Conservative Party and the Canadian Alliance, scored its first-ever victory as they won the greatest number of seats in the House of Commons, winning 124 out of 308, up from 99 seats in 2004.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Due to the emerging details of the sponsorship scandal, as well as a unified right-of-centre party, the Tories led by Stephen Harper went on to end over 12 years of Liberal rule.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper formed the smallest minority government in Canadian history (in terms of proportion of seats), becoming prime minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The New Democratic Party experienced a modest boost in support whereas the Bloc Québécois' seat count nearly stayed the same.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] This is the most recent election in which the winning federal party did not win New Brunswick and Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] This is also the most recent election to have been a direct rematch of the previous one, as none of the four major parties saw a change in leadership between the 2004 and 2006 elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] This unusual winter general election was caused by a motion of no confidence passed by the House of Commons on November 28, 2005, with Canada's three opposition parties contending that the Liberal government of Prime Minister Paul Martin was corrupt.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The following morning Martin met with Governor General Michaëlle Jean, who then dissolved parliament, summoned the next parliament, and ordered the issuance of writs of election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The last set January 23, 2006, as election day and February 13 as the date for return of the writs.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The campaign was almost eight weeks in length, the longest in two decades, in order to allow time for the Christmas and New Year holidays.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Recent political events, most notably testimony to the Gomery Commission investigating the sponsorship scandal, significantly weakened the Liberals (who, under Martin, had formed the first Liberal minority government since the Trudeau era) by allegations of criminal corruption in the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The first Gomery report, released November 1, 2005, had found a "culture of entitlement" to exist within the Government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Although the next election was not legally required until 2009, the opposition had enough votes to force the dissolution of Parliament earlier.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Most observers believed only the Liberals and the Conservatives were capable of forming a government in this election, although Canadian political history is not without examples of wholly unexpected outcomes, such as Ontario's provincial election in 1990.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] However, with the exception of the Unionist government of 1917 (which combined members of both the Conservatives and the Liberals), at the Federal stage, only Liberals or Conservatives have formed government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] With the end of the campaign at hand, pollsters and pundits placed the Conservatives ahead of the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Towards the end of the campaign, even high-profile Liberals were beginning to concede defeat, and the best the Liberals could have achieved was a razor-thin minority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper's Conservatives succeeded in bringing their new party into power in Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] While continuing weaknesses in Quebec and urban areas rightfully prompted most observers to consider a Conservative majority government to be mathematically difficult to achieve, early on, Harper's stated goal was to achieve one nonetheless.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Though the Conservatives were ahead of the Liberals in Quebec, they remained far behind the Bloc Québécois, and additional gains in rural and suburban Ontario would have been necessary to meet Stephen Harper's goal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The polls had remained pretty well static over the course of December, with the real shift coming in the first few days of the New Year.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] That is when the Conservatives took the lead and kept it for the rest of the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper started off the first month of the campaign with a policy-per-day strategy, which included a GST reduction and a child-care allowance.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals opted to hold any major announcements until after the Christmas holidays; as a result, Harper dominated media coverage for the first weeks of the campaign and was able to define his platform and insulate it from expected Liberal attacks.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] On December 27, 2005, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police announced it was investigating allegations that Liberal Finance Minister Ralph Goodale's office had engaged in insider trading before making an important announcement on the taxation of income trusts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The RCMP indicated that they had no evidence of wrongdoing or criminal activity from any party associated with the investigation, including Goodale.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] However, the story dominated news coverage for the following week and prevented the Liberals from making their key policy announcements, allowing the Conservatives to refocus their previous attacks about corruption within the Liberal party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives soon found themselves leading in the polls.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] By early January, they made a major breakthrough in Quebec, pushing the Liberals to second place.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] As their lead solidified, media coverage of the Conservatives was much more positive, while Liberals found themselves increasingly criticized for running a poor campaign and making numerous gaffes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The NDP has claimed that last minute tactical voting cost them several seats last time, as left-of-centre voters moved to the Liberals so that they could prevent a Harper-led government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Jack Layton avoided stating his party's goal was to win the election outright, instead calling for enough New Democrats to be elected to hold the balance of power in a Liberal or Conservative minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Political commentators have long argued that the NDP's main medium-term goal is to serve as junior partners to the Liberals in Canada's first-ever true coalition government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] NDP leader Jack Layton was concerned last time over people voting Liberal so that they could avoid a Conservative government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Over the course of the last week of the campaign, Jack Layton called on Liberal voters disgusted with the corruption to "lend" their votes to the NDP to elect more NDP members to the House and hold the Conservatives to a minority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Bloc Québécois had a very successful result in the 2004 election, with the Liberals reduced to the core areas of federalist support in portions of Montreal and the Outaouais.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Oddly enough, this meant that there were comparatively few winnable Bloc seats left—perhaps eight or so—for the party to target.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] With provincial allies the Parti Québécois widely tipped to regain power in 2007, a large sovereigntist contingent in the House could play a major role in reopening the matter of Quebec independence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Bloc Québécois only runs candidates in the province of Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] However, Gilles Duceppe's dream of winning 50%+ of the popular vote was dashed when the polls broke after the New Year, and the Conservatives became a real threat to that vision in Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In addition to the four sitting parties, the Green Party of Canada ran candidates in all 308 federal ridings for the second consecutive election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Though the Greens had been an official party since the 1984 election, this campaign was the first in which they had stable financial support with which to campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] After a breakthrough in the 2004 election, they exceeded the minimum 2% of the popular vote to receive federal funding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Supporters and sympathisers criticize that the party were not invited to the nationally televised debates even with its official status.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The party has occasionally polled as high as 19% in British Columbia and 11% nationwide.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Critics of the Green Party contended that, by drawing away left-of-centre votes, the Green Party actually assisted the Conservative Party in some ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Other parties are listed in the table of results above.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] An early election seemed likely because the 2004 federal election, held on June 28, 2004, resulted in the election of a Liberal minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In the past, minority governments have had an average lifespan of a year and a half.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Some people considered the 38th parliament to be particularly unstable.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] It involved four parties, and only very implausible ideological combinations (e.g., Liberals + Conservatives; Liberals + BQ; Conservatives + BQ + NDP) could actually command a majority of the seats, a necessity if a government is to retain power.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] From its earliest moments, there was some threat of the government falling as even the Speech from the Throne almost resulted in a non-confidence vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberal government came close to falling when testimony from the Gomery Commission caused public opinion to move sharply against the government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Bloc Québécois were eager from the beginning to have an early election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives announced they had also lost confidence in the government's moral authority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Thus, during much of spring 2005, there was a widespread belief that the Liberals would lose a confidence vote, prompting an election taking place in the spring or summer of 2005.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In a televised speech on April 21, Martin promised to request a dissolution of Parliament and begin an election campaign within 30 days of the Gomery Commission's final report.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The release date of that report would later solidify as February 1, 2006; Martin then clarified that he intended to schedule the election call so as to have the polling day in April 2006.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Later that week, the NDP, who had initially opposed the budget, opted to endorse Martin's proposal for a later election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals agreed to take corporate tax cuts out of the budget on April 26 in exchange for NDP support on votes of confidence, but even with NDP support the Liberals still fell three votes short of a majority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] However, a surprise defection of former Conservative leadership candidate Belinda Stronach to the Liberal party on May 17 changed the balance of power in the House.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Independents Chuck Cadman and Carolyn Parrish provided the last two votes needed for the Liberals to win the budget vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The deal turned out to be rather unnecessary, as the Conservatives opted to ensure the government's survival on the motion of confidence surrounding the original budget, expressing support to the tax cuts and defence spending therein.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] When Parliament voted on second reading and referral of the budget and the amendment on May 19, the previous events kept the government alive.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The original budget bill, C-43, passed easily, as expected, but the amendment bill, C-48, resulted in an equality of votes, and the Speaker of the House broke the tie to continue the parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The government never got as close to falling after that date.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Third reading of Bill C-48 was held late at night on an unexpected day, and several Conservatives being absent, the motion passed easily, guaranteeing there would be no election in the near future.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] On November 1, John Gomery released his interim report, and the scandal returned to prominence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Liberal support again fell, with some polls registering an immediate ten percent drop.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives and Bloc thus resumed their push for an election before Martin's April date.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The NDP stated that their support was contingent on the Liberals agreeing to move against the private provision of healthcare.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals and NDP failed to come to an agreement, however, and the NDP joined the two other opposition parties in demanding an election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] However, the Liberals had intentionally scheduled the mandatory "opposition days" (where a specified opposition party controls the agenda) on November 15 (Conservative), November 17 (Bloc Québécois) and November 24 (NDP).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] These days meant that any election would come over the Christmas season, an unpopular idea.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Following negotiations between the opposition parties, they instead issued an ultimatum to the Prime Minister to call an election immediately after the Christmas holidays or face an immediate non-confidence vote which would prompt a holiday-spanning campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Martin had indicated that he remained committed to his April 2006 date, and would disregard the motion, which the opposition parties managed to pass, as expected, on November 21 by a vote of 167–129.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The three opposition leaders had agreed to delay the tabling of the no-confidence motion until the 24th, to ensure that a conference between the government and aboriginal leaders scheduled on the 24th would not be disrupted by the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Parliamentary procedure dictated that the vote be deferred until the 28th.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Even if the opposition had not put forward the non-confidence motion, the government was still expected to fall—there was to have been a vote on supplementary budget estimates on December 8, and if it had been defeated, loss of Supply would have toppled the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Conservative leader Stephen Harper, the leader of the Opposition, introduced a motion of no confidence on November 24, which NDP leader Jack Layton seconded.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] One Bloc Québécois MP was absent from the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] It is the fifth time a Canadian government has lost the confidence of Parliament, but the first time this has happened on a straight motion of no confidence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The four previous instances have been due to loss of supply or votes of censure.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Martin visited Governor General Michaëlle Jean the following morning, where he formally advised her to dissolve Parliament and schedule an election for January 23.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In accordance with Canadian constitutional practice, she consented (such a request has only been turned down once in Canadian history), officially beginning an election campaign that had been simmering for months.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Early on in the campaign, polls showed the Liberals with a solid 5–10 point lead over the Conservatives, and poised to form a strong minority government at worst.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Around Christmas, after reports of an RCMP investigation into allegations of insider trading within the Finance department, this situation changed dramatically, leading to the opposition parties consistently attacking the Liberals on corruption.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Almost at the same time, the Boxing Day shooting, an unusually violent gun fight between rival gangs on December 26 in downtown Toronto (resulting in the death of 15-year-old Jane Creba, an innocent bystander), may have swayed some Ontario voters to support the more hardline CPC policies on crime.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives enjoyed a fairly significant lead in polls leading up to the election, but the gap narrowed in the last few days.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Elections Canada later investigated improper election spending by the Conservative Party, which became widely known as the In and Out scandal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In 2011, charges against senior Conservatives were dropped in a plea deal that saw the party and its fundraising arm plead guilty and receive the maximum possible fines, totaling $52,000.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Prior to and during the election campaign, opinion polling showed variable support for the governing Liberals and opposition Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In November 2005, the first report by Justice John Gomery was released to the public; subsequently, poll numbers for the Liberals again dropped.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Just days later, polling showed the Liberals were already bouncing back; upon the election call, the Liberals held a small lead over the Conservatives and maintained this for much of December.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Ultimately this scandal was linked to a blackberry exchange to a banking official by Liberal candidate Scott Brison.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Polling figures for the NDP increased slightly, while Bloc figures experienced a slight dip; figures for the Green Party did not change appreciably throughout the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] An exit poll was carried out by Ipsos Reid polling firm.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The poll overestimated the NDP's support and underestimated the Liberals' support.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The election involved the same 308 electoral districts as in 2004, except in New Brunswick, where the boundary between Acadie—Bathurst and Miramichi was ruled to be illegal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Many of the candidates were also the same: fewer incumbents chose to leave than if they had served a full term, and the parties have generally blocked challenges to sitting MPs for the duration of the minority government, although there had been some exceptions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] An ongoing issue in Canadian politics is the imbalance between the genders in selection by political parties of candidates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] Although in the past some parties, particularly the New Democrats, have focused on the necessity of having equal gender representation in Parliament, no major party has ever nominated as many or more women than men in a given election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] In 2006, the New Democrats had the highest percentage of female candidates (35.1%) of any party aside from the Animal Alliance, which only had one candidate, its leader, Liz White.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] The proportion of female New Democrats elected was greater than the proportion nominated, indicating female New Democrats were nominated in winnable ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p01] 12.3% of Conservative candidates and 25.6% of Liberal candidates were female.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] The election was held on January 23, 2006.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] ET (0000 UTC); Elections Canada started to publish preliminary results on its website at 10:00 p.m.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Harper was reelected in Calgary Southwest, which he has held since 2002, ensuring that he had a seat in the new parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Shortly after midnight (ET) that night, incumbent Prime Minister Paul Martin conceded defeat, and announced that he would resign as leader of the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] At 9:30 a.m. on January 24, Martin informed Governor General Michaëlle Jean that he would not form a government and intended to resign as Prime Minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later that day, at 6:45 p.m., Jean invited Harper to form a government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Martin formally resigned and Harper was formally appointed and sworn in as Prime Minister on February 6.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Harper became the first leader of a political party to lead it to victory following a loss in the previous election since Wilfrid Laurier in 1896.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] It was announced a month later that there would be a Liberal leadership convention later in the year, during which Stéphane Dion won the leadership of the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Martin continued to sit as a Member of Parliament representing LaSalle—Émard, the Montreal-area riding he had held since 1988, until his retirement in 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] The elections resulted in a Conservative minority government with 124 seats in parliament with a Liberal opposition and a strengthened NDP.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] In his speech following the loss, Martin stated he would not lead the Liberal Party of Canada in another election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Preliminary results indicated that 64.9% of registered voters cast a ballot, a notable increase over 2004's 60.9%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] The NDP won new seats in British Columbia and Ontario as their overall popular vote increased 2% from 2004.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Bloc managed to win almost as many seats as in 2004 despite losing a significant percentage of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Most of the Conservatives' gains were in rural Ontario and Quebec as they took a net loss in the west, but won back the only remaining Liberal seat in Alberta.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] The popular vote of the Conservatives and Liberals were almost the mirror image of 2004, though the Conservatives were not able to translate this into as many seats as the Liberals did in 2004.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] A judicial recount was automatically scheduled in the Parry Sound-Muskoka riding, where early results showed Conservative Tony Clement only 21 votes ahead of Liberal Andy Mitchell, because the difference of votes cast between the two leading candidates was less than 0.1%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Clement was confirmed as the winner by 28 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] Conservative candidate Jeremy Harrison, narrowly defeated by Liberal Gary Merasty in the Saskatchewan riding of Desnethé—Missinippi—Churchill River by 72 votes, alleged electoral fraud but decided not to pursue the matter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p02] A judicial recount was ordered in the riding, which certified Gary Merasty the winner by a reduced margin of 68 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Brenda Locke was a member of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Bev Desjarlais, the incumbent elected under the NDP banner, received 4,283 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Jean-Pierre Ouellet was a member of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Danny Gay was a member of the Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Greg Kerr was a member of the Nova Scotia House of Assembly.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Marilyn Churley was a member of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Irene Mathyssen was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Terence Young was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] John Baird was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario and a provincial Cabinet minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Tony Clement was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario and a provincial Cabinet minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Jacques Léonard was previously a member of the National Assembly of Quebec and a provincial Cabinet minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2006-canadian-federal-election-p03] Lawrence Cannon was previously a member of the National Assembly of Quebec and a provincial Cabinet minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Twelve vacancies occurred during the life of the Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Nine of these were filled by by-elections and the remaining three were filled at the 2008 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Two federal by-elections were held in Canada on November 27, 2006, to fill vacancies in the House of Commons of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Both seats were held by their incumbent parties.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Long-time MP Joe Fontana resigned from the seat in 2006, in order to run in the London municipal election as a candidate for mayor, requiring a by-election to be held.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The election result presented a major breakthrough for the Green Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Party leader Elizabeth May tripled the party's local result in the 2006 general election just ten months earlier, placing slightly ahead of former London mayor Dianne Haskett, the candidate of the governing Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] MP Benoît Sauvageau was killed in a car accident on August 28, 2006.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] There had been pressure from opposition parties for Public Works Minister Michael Fortier, a Conservative senator, to run here — however, he declined.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Fortier was appointed to the Senate and the Cabinet to represent Greater Montreal, which elected no Conservatives in the last federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Fortier pledged to resign from the Senate and seek election to the House of Commons in the next federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Instead, the Conservative candidate was Stéphane Bourgon, a lawyer.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Bloc Québécois, of which Sauvageau was a member, ran Raymond Gravel, a Roman Catholic priest.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The New Democratic Party candidate was union activist and former Canadian navy member Réjean Bellemare, who had also run for the NDP in the previous general election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Green Party of Canada had announced that Marc-André Gadoury would be their candidate, but central office did not complete and send paperwork to Marc-André Gadoury, not to name leader signature, in sufficient time to get on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Gadoury suggested that the Greens did not submit the paperwork on purpose and on November 25, 2006, *La Presse* reported that Gadoury was endorsing the NDP candidate, Réjean Bellemare.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Raymond Gravel of the Bloc Québécois won the by-election with an approximately two-thirds majority of votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] On September 17, 2007, three federal by-elections were held in the Canadian province of Quebec to fill vacancies in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Each of the three by-elections was won by a different political party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The by-elections in Outremont and Saint-Hyacinthe—Bagot were originally announced by Prime Minister Stephen Harper on July 28, 2007.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The third vacancy, in Roberval—Lac-Saint-Jean, occurred after the other two by-election campaigns were already underway, but Harper announced the by-election in that riding on August 11, scheduling it for the same date.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of Outremont was left vacant by the resignation of Liberal Party MP Jean Lapierre.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The by-election resulted in a victory for the New Democratic Party on a substantial swing, whose candidate Thomas Mulcair became only the second New Democrat ever elected from Quebec and the first in seventeen years.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Saint-Hyacinthe—Bagot by-election and the Roberval—Lac-Saint-Jean by-election were held on the same day.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The by-election was triggered when Lapierre resigned from the House on January 28, to accept a position as a political analyst with Quebec television network TVA and Montreal radio station 98.5 FM.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Prime Minister of Canada has six months to call by-elections, and Prime Minister Stephen Harper called the by-election on the last possible day, July 28.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Finally, Liberal leader Stéphane Dion appointed candidate Jocelyn Coulon on July 18.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Liberal announcement was not without controversy, and was condemned by Jewish lobby group B'nai Brith, even asking for the nomination to be revoked.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The group cited Coulon's views on Israel, the United States and Hamas as being "out of step with current Liberal policy." The Quebec-Israel Committee stated that B'nai Brith's statements were exaggerated and that Coulon had every right to be the Liberal candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Though the riding is only 10 per cent Jewish, past Liberal candidates have traditionally relied heavily on the faithful support of this important voting block.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Bloc Québécois, which came in second in the seat in 2006, selected Belgian-born, Lacanian psychoanalyst Jean-Paul Gilson as their candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The New Democratic Party, third place in 2006, selected Thomas Mulcair.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Mulcair is a former Liberal Member of the National Assembly of Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] He served as Jean Charest's Minister of the Environment from 2003 to 2006, leaving cabinet amidst the controversy surrounding privatisation plans for Mont Orford provincial park.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] He was the MNA for Chomedey in Laval, Quebec from 1994 to 2007.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] On April 20, Mulcair announced he was joining the New Democratic Party during a joint press conference with NDP Leader Jack Layton on Mont Royal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] He currently serves as the NDP's Quebec spokesperson.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Mulcair was nominated in an uncontested race on June 21 as the NDP candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Conservatives selected former Ambassador Gilles Duguay.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Green Party, fifth place in 2006, reselected their 2006 candidate, François Pilon, while the Canadian Action Party selected biochemistry student Alexandre Amirizian.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The newly formed neorhino.ca, successor to the Rhinoceros Party of Canada, fielded party founder François Gourd on August 7.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Gourd wished to finish last in the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The electoral district of Roberval—Lac-Saint-Jean was left vacant by the resignation of Michel Gauthier (Bloc).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Although Gauthier resigned after the other two by-elections had already been called, Prime Minister Stephen Harper announced the by-election on August 11 for the same date as the others.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Notably, Roberval—Lac-Saint-Jean was a district which the Tories had heavily targeted in the 2006 election but had narrowly lost.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] It was seen as the district most likely to be winnable for the party in the by-elections — and thus the by-election Harper was most eager to actually schedule.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The by-election in Saint-Hyacinthe—Bagot, resulting from the resignation of Yvan Loubier, was won by BQ candidate Ève-Mary Thaï Thi Lac, Loubier's former constituency assistant and the first Vietnamese Canadian ever elected to the House of Commons of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] However, Thi Lac's 1,478-vote margin of victory over Conservative candidate Bernard Barré was the narrowest victory for the BQ since the party first won the riding in the 1993 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] As in the other two ridings up for election, the Liberals were shut out; their candidate, Jean Caumartin, placed fourth, after the NDP's Brigitte Sansoucy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Four **federal by-elections** were held in Canada on March 17, 2008 to fill vacancies in the House of Commons of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The vacancies were caused by the resignations of Liberal MPs Gary Merasty (Desnethé—Missinippi—Churchill River), Bill Graham (Toronto Centre), Stephen Owen (Vancouver Quadra) and Jim Peterson (Willowdale).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] However, the four by-elections scheduled for September were pre-empted by the issuance on September 7 of election writs for the 2008 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] With all four by-elections taking place in ridings previously held by the Liberals, media generally treated them as a test of Stéphane Dion's leadership.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Desnethé—Missinippi—Churchill River** became vacant on August 31, 2007 with the resignation of Liberal MP Gary Merasty.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] David Orchard, a former member of the Progressive Conservative Party of Canada and backer of Stéphane Dion during the Liberal leadership contest, had announced that he would seek the Liberal nomination in Desnethé—Missinippi—Churchill River.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] However, on January 3, 2008, Dion used his power of appointment to appoint Joan Beatty as the Liberal candidate for that riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] While Dion had stated several times that he would use his power of appointment to ensure more female candidates, many felt the appointment was a snub to his erstwhile supporter and media reports suggested that Ralph Goodale, a prominent Saskatchewan MP, opposed Orchard's candidacy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Beatty, who was a New Democratic Party MLA in the Saskatchewan legislature until her federal candidacy was announced, also faced some criticism, both for her switch in party affiliations and for resigning to run federally just seven weeks after being reelected in the 2007 provincial election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Some Liberal Party members in the riding threatened to boycott the by-election entirely, or to vote for another party, if Dion did not rescind the appointment and allow a normal nomination contest to take place.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Toronto Centre** became vacant on July 2, 2007, with the resignation of Liberal MP Bill Graham.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The original Conservative candidate, Mark Warner, was dropped by the party's national council on October 31, 2007, reportedly for not following party policy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Warner eventually endorsed Rae rather than his replacement as Conservative candidate, Don Meredith, after Meredith reportedly told a voter who asked him a question about the ongoing bedbug problem in the St.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Jamestown neighbourhood to improve their personal hygiene.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Vancouver Quadra** became vacant on July 27, 2007 with the resignation of Liberal MP Stephen Owen.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Joyce Murray won the Liberal nomination in the riding and faced a hard-fought campaign against Conservative challenger Deborah Meredith.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Murray, originally an MLA and former provincial cabinet minister from New Westminster, grew up in the riding, but recently moved back to run for federal office.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Her campaign was focussed on environmental issues.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Meredith is a UBC law lecturer and has lived in Vancouver Quadra her whole life, campaigned primarily on a tougher judicial system.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] NDP candidate and UBC student Rebecca Coad focussed her attacks on Murray, criticizing her record as provincial environment minister in Gordon Campbell's government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Green Party candidate Dan Grice, a technology consultant, ran a campaign based on cutting down on carbon emissions and tax shifting, hoping for an electoral breakthrough for his party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] On election day, early results showed Murray and Meredith in a dead heat, see-saw race.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Later in the night, Murray was able to capture a more comfortable lead of several hundred votes, and the media declared her the winner.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] However, as the advanced polls were opened and counted, Meredith started to close the gap.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] After all 237 polls were counted, Murray remained in the lead, finishing with a narrow 151 (0.53%) vote margin above her Conservative opponent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Willowdale** became vacant on July 12, 2007 with the resignation of Liberal MP Jim Peterson.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Martha Hall Findlay, former Liberal leadership contestant, was a star candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] She faced Conservative lawyer Maureen Harquail, NDP candidate Rini Ghosh, and Green candidate Lou Carcasole.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] On election night, Hall Findlay garnered nearly 60% of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Four by-elections scheduled for September 2008 were pre-empted by the issuance on September 7 of election writs for the 2008 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] In all four ridings, the by-election candidates continued to represent their parties into the general election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Westmount—Ville-Marie** had been vacant since January 25, 2008 due to the resignation of Liberal MP Lucienne Robillard.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The nominated candidates were Marc Garneau (Liberal), Charles Larivée (Bloc Québécois), Guy Dufort (Conservative), Anne Lagacé Dowson (New Democrat), Claude William Genest (Green) and independents Régent Millette, David Sommer Rovins and Ronald Andrew Wattie.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The by-election was scheduled for September 8.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Saint-Lambert** had been vacant since March 13, 2008 due to Bloc Québécois MP Maka Kotto's resignation in order to run for a seat in the Quebec National Assembly.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Kotto was elected to the National Assembly in a May 12, 2008 provincial by-election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The NDP nominated Richard Marois, president of the Conseil régional de l'environnement de la Montérégie, the Liberals ran lawyer and Crown attorney Roxane Stanners, the Conservative candidate was Patrick Clune, and the Greens nominated occupational therapist Diane Joubert.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Guelph** was held by Liberal Brenda Chamberlain, until she resigned her seat effective April 7, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Conservative candidate was originally businessman Brent Barr, but his candidacy was rejected by the party in October without specific reasons for the move being made public.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The riding of **Don Valley West** was held by Liberal John Godfrey who initially said he would resign from the House of Commons on July 1, 2008 in order to accept a position as headmaster of Toronto French School, but delayed his resignation until August 1.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The delay was reportedly at the request of the Liberal Party which, the *National Post* claimed did not want to fight four by-elections simultaneously for financial reasons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Godfrey's office stated the delay was due to a private members bill Godfrey had worked on not being given royal assent until June 26.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] This by-election was scheduled for September 22.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Due to the timing of Godfrey's retirement, the Don Valley West by-election could not have been added to the September 8 trio.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Under current Canadian election law, a by-election cannot occur any earlier than 47 working days (an 11-day period to ensure that Elections Canada has been notified of the vacancy, plus a minimum 36-day campaign) after a vacancy occurs in the House.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Rob Oliphant was nominated as the Liberal Party's standard-bearer on March 2, 2008 after defeating former Parkdale—High Park MP Sarmite Bulte for the nomination on the fourth ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] Constitutional lawyer Deborah Coyne had also contested the nomination but withdrew in February and backed Oliphant.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-by-elections] The Conservative Party of Canada re-nominated 2006 candidate John Carmichael, the New Democratic Party nominated actor David Sparrow, while the Green Party nominated Georgina Wilcock, a medical doctor with specialist training in obstetrics and gynecology.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The **2008 Canadian federal election** was held on October 14, 2008, to elect members to the House of Commons of Canada of the 40th Canadian Parliament after the previous parliament had been dissolved by Governor General Michaëlle Jean on September 7, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The election resulted in a second but stronger minority government for Harper's Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] While they were a dozen seats away from a majority government, the Liberal Party led by Stéphane Dion lost 18 seats as the New Democratic Party and the Bloc Québécois made slight gains.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Green Party failed to win any seats and lost its only Member of Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Following the election, the Liberals and New Democrats attempted to form a coalition government and topple the Conservatives from power, but were unsuccessful in doing so.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] With a turnout of 58.8% of eligible voters, this election had the lowest in Canadian federal election history, and to date is the only time it has ever dipped below the 60% threshold.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] This was the first election since 1988 in which a centre-right party won the most seats in Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In this election there was no loss of a non-confidence vote, but the Prime Minister asked the Governor General to call an election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Governor General granted the Prime Minister's request.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] 64.7% of eligible voters cast ballots in the 2006 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservative Party received the most votes of any single party, with 36% of the vote, and won 124 seats (127 at dissolution).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberal Party won fewer seats than in 2004 – 103 seats (96 at dissolution), and 30% of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Bloc Québécois lost three seats, lowering its total to 51 seats (48 at dissolution), with 10.5% of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The NDP retained its seats held at the dissolution of Parliament, and won 11 more, making its total 29 seats (30 at dissolution), with 17.5% of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Green Party received 4.5% of the vote, a minimal increase from the previous election, but did not win any seats (1 at dissolution).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Independents and other parties constituted 1% of the total vote with one independent winning a seat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In by-elections, the NDP gained one seat from the Liberal Party, while the Conservative Party gained two seats, one from the Liberals and one from the Bloc Québécois.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Four seats were vacant when the election was called: three previously held by the Liberal Party, one by the Bloc Québécois.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The parliament preceding this election was led by the Conservatives, who governed with the smallest plurality ever in the Canadian House of Commons, just 40.6% of the seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The 39th Parliament became Canada's longest serving Conservative minority on October 24, 2006.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On May 30, 2006, the Conservatives tabled An Act to Amend the Canada Elections Act, which would amend the Canada Elections Act to provide fixed election dates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The bill received royal assent on May 3, 2007.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The bill stated that there would be an election in 2009, and it would be the first to have a fixed election date, the third Monday in October (October 19, 2009).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Despite the bill, on September 7, 2008, the Prime Minister sought the dissolution of the 39th Parliament, and the Governor General agreed to hold a general election on October 14, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On February 15, 2007, *The Globe and Mail* reported that the Conservatives were preparing for an election expected to be called shortly after the 2007 budget, due on March 19, 2007.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Part of the reason for the timing of the election was given as strengthening Conservative poll numbers coupled with the desire to take advantage of the perception that Harper has "better leadership qualities than Liberal counterpart Stéphane Dion".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On March 17, 2007, an internal Conservative Party memo was leaked to *The Canadian Press*, telling members that they "need to be ready to campaign within the next week".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The memo asked members to donate $75 to $150 to help to fund the early stages of the election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] None of these predictions for a federal election to occur in 2007 proved true, but the majority of pundits still believed a federal election would be triggered before the fixed election date of October 19, 2009, for sometime in 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper hinted at the possibility of dissolving parliament on August 14, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Speaking in Newfoundland and Labrador, he cited Stéphane Dion as the main player in making Parliament become increasingly "dysfunctional".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] "I'm going to have to make a judgment in the next little while as to whether or not this Parliament can function productively," Harper said.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] This came after repeated confidence votes that resulted in the NDP and Bloc parties not voting in favour of the government, and the Liberal Party voting in favour or not attending the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Rumours of a possible fall election were further fuelled by Harper's announcement of a fourth federal by-election for September 22 in the Toronto riding of Don Valley West.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On August 27, 2008, Harper asked Governor General Michaëlle Jean to cancel her trip to the Paralympic Games in Beijing, adding fuel to speculation that the Prime Minister would seek a dissolution.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 7, 2008, after much speculation, Harper asked the Governor General to call a federal election on October 14, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In August 2008, Prime Minister Stephen Harper said he was considering calling an election because of a lack of cooperation in Parliament, saying "all the signs indicate that this Parliament is at the end of its productiveness," while in Inuvik, Northwest Territories.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservative Party of Canada fueled rumours of an oncoming election when it released several campaign advertisements that focused on a range of issues, and attacked the Liberal Party of Canada for their proposed carbon tax.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Senior government officials announced on the first of September that Stephen Harper would ask the Governor General, Michaëlle Jean, to dissolve parliament and call an election for October 14, after he met with Liberal leader Stéphane Dion who called the meeting a "charade".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion said the two were unable to agree on how to make the upcoming session of Parliament, slated to begin September 15, more productive.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Liberal Party members gathered in Winnipeg on September 2, for a three-day caucus which changed from preparing for a new parliamentary session to a strategy session to formulate a plan to attack the Conservatives while healing internal party rifts that have surfaced in recent weeks.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Conservatives began spending at least $60 million on pre-election funding projects to a wide variety of institutions and groups.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] A few announcements have been big, including Industry Minister Jim Prentice's pledge of $25 million for the expansion of the Northlands exhibition facility in Edmonton.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] But the Tories have also announced a number of smaller projects, including $40,000 for the 2008 55+ Games and $25,000 for the Peace Window of the Holy Trinity Anglican Church in Winnipeg.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The announcements have also been spread out across the country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Atlantic region is to get more than $500,000 for youth jobs and eight cultural organizations.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Association of Book Publishers of British Columbia will receive $81,000.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Jack Layton attacked the Conservative Party as bribing the public and doing the same thing they used to complain about the Liberals doing before elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] A survey conducted by Environics found that 38 per cent of Canadians would vote for the Conservative party if an election were held immediately, 28 per cent would vote for the Liberal party, 19 for the NDP, eight for the Bloc Québécois and seven for the Green party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The poll shows Conservatives taking early leads in Ontario, British Columbia and the Prairies.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In Atlantic Canada, Liberals still hold a strong majority, while in Quebec the Bloc Québécois leads while the Conservatives and Liberals are almost tied for second.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] When asked, most Canadians said the Conservatives would handle the economy better, while most said the Liberals would handle the environment better.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 7, Harper officially asked for the dissolution of Parliament, and called for an election on October 14.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The 40th Canadian Federal Election campaign officially began at 8:20 a.m.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Eastern Daylight Time when Governor General Michaëlle Jean accepted Stephen Harper's request to dissolve Parliament and call an election for October 14, 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The party leaders jumped right into the campaign, with Stéphane Dion attacking the Conservatives' record, presenting the Liberal plan, and rejected the accusation by Harper that the Liberal party is a risky choice.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Jack Layton took a more forceful approach than previous elections, in which the New Democratic Party has just tried to maintain a high number of seats in Parliament to influence government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton has made it clear he will campaign for the position of prime minister itself this time, but also returned to a longstanding NDP theme: alleged abuses by big business.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] He promised to stop what he called "ripoffs" by big oil, cellphone and banks, and his attacks are expected to focus on the Conservatives and all but ignore the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Elizabeth May of the Green Party said Canadians would care enough about the environment to vote for her party, as long as she was able to get into the television debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper has stated his objection to including the Green Party into television debates because of the similar policies of the Green and Liberal party, and how it would be unfair.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bloc Québécois Leader Gilles Duceppe said the Conservatives must be prevented from winning a majority, and the BQ is the only party that can do that.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Duceppe compared Harper to US President George W.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bush, and said the government is incompetent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The two Leaders' Debates of 2008, one each in French and English, included the leaders of five parties, Stephen Harper of the Conservatives, Stéphane Dion of the Liberals, Jack Layton of the NDP, Gilles Duceppe of the Bloc Québécois and Elizabeth May of the Green Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The French-language debate aired on Wednesday, October 1 from 8 to 10 p.m.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] EDT, moderated by Stéphan Bureau, a journalist and host.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The English-language debate aired Thursday, October 2 from 9 to 11 p.m.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] EDT, with Steve Paikin of TVOntario as moderator.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper and Jack Layton are reported to have said that if the Green Party were included, they would not participate in the Leaders' Debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion said that while he supports May's inclusion, he would not attend if Harper does not, and the Bloc Québécois has stated it will not boycott the debates if May is included.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The media consortium in charge of the debate, made up of the CBC, CTV, Global Television and TVA, had decided that it would prefer to broadcast the debates with the four major party leaders, rather than risk not at all or with minimal participation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Green Party indicated they had begun procedures to lodge a formal complaint with the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission, as they have in past federal elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 10, Harper and Layton released statements that they would not oppose May's inclusion in the debate, citing public backlash and protests — with neither acknowledging making the threat of boycotting the debate — and that the media consortium would reconvene to discuss the matter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton stated that "debating about the debate" had become a "distraction", and that he had only one condition, that Stephen Harper be there.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In response, spokespeople for Stephen Harper announced they would not stand alone in opposition to the Green Party's inclusion in the debates and also changed their position on the matter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Later that day the consortium announced that May would be allowed to participate in the debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The NDP released a statement soon after that they supported the move, while public response has been concerned that other topics such as the environment would not end up with enough time to cover the issue.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On October 1, the day of the first debate, it was announced that both debates would get extended time, from 12 to 30 minutes, for the economy, and leaders would not give opening and closing statements, to allow for longer discussions on the economy without removing time from other topics.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] It was also revealed that instead of leaders standing at individual podiums for the debate, as had been done in past years, the debate would be done in a round table format.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Much of the French debate revolved around the economy and the environment, with the two topics repeatedly being brought up in discussions allotted for other topics.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper came under criticism from every other leader in nearly every topic, especially the economy and environment, with the other party leaders stating that Harper's politics had led to Canada's current crises in those two areas.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Continuous comparisons of Harper to George W.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bush were made over the course of the debate, with Jack Layton stating at one point that with Bush ending his presidency at the end of the year, Harper would be "the last leader of a developed country to follow the Bush doctrine".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Following the same tone as the French debate, much of the discussion revolved around the economy and the environment.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The other four leaders keep criticizing Harper, especially for his lack of an economic platform despite asking for the format change to focus more on the economy due to the Great Recession, and instead using the time to criticize the economic platforms of the other leaders.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper also came under criticism for his laissez-faire attitude to the job sector, supporting primarily the oil companies and companies that outsource jobs in the manufacturing sector.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper criticized the plan, saying would increase taxpayers' burden and that Dion should be "honest with the people" that some environmental measures will cost the economy and said the plan includes $40 billion in carbon taxes and $26 billion in tax cuts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion defended the Liberals' Green Shift, saying that "[Harper's statements are] not true at all", and that "for every dollar that we will raise, you will have a tax cut, and these tax cuts will be on your income".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Duceppe commented that he would like targets to be applied to individual provinces, thereby allowing Quebec to financially benefit due to already-implemented greenhouse gas reductions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton, who favours a cap-and-trade system, said that it is a "figment of Mr.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper's imagination" that emissions will fall under his plan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton also criticized Dion for his lack of accomplishments as official opposition during the minority government, and his party's previous leader's broken promises in areas such as Child Care and Pharmacare.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper also said he had erred in calling for Canada's participation in the 2003 U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, saying "It was absolutely an error, it's obviously clear", adding that the claim of weapons of mass destruction proved false.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Commenting on the debate, Layton said that he "thoroughly enjoyed" May's contributions to the debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Reporter Julie Van Dusen said that Harper managed to take the hits calmly, as "someone must have told him ... if you fight back or get too partisan, you're going to alienate voters, especially women".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper had cut $45 million from arts funding while in office, a move that drew much criticism from the other leaders and Quebec citizens, with most leaders seeking to restore the funding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper has said that he believes that the issue is a "niche topic", and that "ordinary Canadians" are not particularly concerned with the issue.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] A group of Canadian performers, which included Art Hindle, Wendy Crewson and Gordon Pinsent, held a press conference on September 24, saying the cuts would cripple the Canadian arts industry.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 29, Harper unveiled a new tax credit plan worth an estimated $150 million a year to encourage parents to enroll their kids in arts programs like music and drama.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The credit will apply on up to $500 of eligible fees for children under 16 who participate in eligible arts activities.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper said that "[the Conservatives] spend a lot more on culture and arts" but "in a way that we ensure is an effective use of taxpayers' money and ultimately, in this case, benefits families and all of society as well".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper has come under criticism when the week before he expressed his opinion that "ordinary working people were unable to relate to taxpayer-subsidized cultural elites when they see them at a rich gala on television".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In early 2008 it was alleged that Independent MP Chuck Cadman of Surrey North, who was terminally ill with cancer at the time, had been offered a million dollar life insurance policy in exchange for voting against the proposed Liberal budget in May 2005, which he turned down.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Under section 119 of the Criminal Code, it is illegal to bribe an MP.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Accordingly, Opposition Liberal party Intergovernmental Affairs critic Dominic LeBlanc asked the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) in February 2008 to investigate this allegation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In May 2008, the RCMP announced that there was not enough evidence to support charges.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The following month, Harper stated in a court deposition that any such million-dollar offer would have to be authorized by him, and that he did not issue any such authorization.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] There is currently an ongoing legal battle between the Liberals and the Conservatives over the matter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 24, while campaigning in Surrey North, Stephen Harper's campaign team barred reporters from talking with the local Conservative candidate, Dona Cadman, who is Chuck Cadman's widow.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The campaign team called in the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP), and ordered them to "Keep [the reporters] out" while Cadman was taken away by staff.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Federal Bureau of Investigation agent Bruce Koenig to analyze a tape of reporter Tom Zytaruk interviewing Harper on the Cadman bribe attempt.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The tape was a key piece of evidence in the ongoing legal battle.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On October 10, Koenig announced that the tape had not been altered in any way, contrary to the claims by Stephen Harper that it had been altered.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The ongoing involvement of the Canadian Forces in Afghanistan may also influence voters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Miller stated he will not endorse a specific party, but urges people to choose a party that will "help cities thrive".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] He disagrees with Stephen Harper's opinion that "cities are not of national importance".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper immediately lashed out at the spending proposal, saying Dion was "promising money no government could afford" and that the Conservatives' infrastructure plans "are modest and affordable within the four-year budget we've published".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Jean Perrault, president of the Federation of Canadian Municipalities and mayor of Sherbrooke, Quebec, has stated that things like the Federal Gas Tax Fund were an important federal commitment, but that more is needed to tackle cities' overwhelming infrastructure needs.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Polls have suggested that the economy is the major issue going into this election, especially with the resulting high price of gas, along with rising prices of other goods and services, such as food, and the possible impact the 2008 financial crisis may have on Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Some experts say that Canada has just narrowly dodged a recession, although the economy is in its worst shape since 1991.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Both Dion and Harper have said that the others' plans will lead Canada into a recession, while Dion also stated that Harper has "mismanaged a once-booming economy into one with growth dropping to among the lowest of the G8 nations".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives have stated possible negative consequences that could happen to the economy based on Liberal election promises if they were to be elected.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] As of September 20, 2008, Liberal election promises have totaled in excess of $80 billion spending over the next decade.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In contrast, the cost of programs promised by the Conservatives to date is less than $2 billion annually.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Stephen Harper, the Prime Minister, has criticized the Liberals' spending promises, saying they are making "mind-boggling" spending plans that he predicts would send Canada into deficit.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] All the leaders supported the idea, and the opening and closing statements were dropped and the allotted time for the economy extended to 30 minutes without affecting the other topics.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In response to mounting pressure from the public, Harper announced on October 3 that he would reveal his party's platform, including economic matters, on October 7, one week before the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Shortly after the election was called, Harper was criticized for using a four-vehicle motorcade that included a van and SUV to travel the 395 m (1,296 ft) across the street from the door of 24 Sussex Drive to the door of Rideau Hall to dissolve parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In return, the Conservatives criticized the Liberal party's decision to use a 29-year-old Boeing 737-200 for campaigning, saying that the older airplane's poor fuel efficiency demonstrates hypocrisy on environmental matters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Daniel Lauzon, a spokesperson for the Liberals, denied their airplane was substantially less efficient than the Conservatives' Airbus A319.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Tories have been previously criticized for backing out of Canada's commitments under the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Their new plan requires industries to reduce the rate at which they generate greenhouse gases, with a goal of reducing overall emissions by 45 to 65 percent by 2050.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The plan has been criticized by groups such as the Sierra Club, who called it "completely inadequate".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Criticism has focused on the use of "intensity-based" targets, for which emission reductions are relative to overall production, so overall emissions could potentially increase if production also increases.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] This is in contrast to a "hard cap" on emissions, for which the overall amount cannot increase.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives' plan includes a hard cap to begin in 2020 or 2025, while environmental groups have advocated for an immediate hard cap.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals have developed a "Green Shift" plan, creating a carbon tax that will be coupled with reductions to income tax rates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The proposal was to tax greenhouse gas emissions, starting at $10 (Canadian) per ton of CO2 and reaching $40 (Canadian) per ton within four years.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The plan would engage in revenue recycling by matching the tax with reductions in the income tax.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Criticism of the Green Shift plan has focused on its economic effects, with the Conservatives predicting it would cause a "big recession".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] When pressed by reporters to provide evidence of this impact, Harper "wasn't able to cite a study that specifically modelled the impact of the Liberal Green Shift plan", instead citing an older economic model about the implementation of the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] One trucking association claimed the Liberal carbon tax plan could put up to 10,000 jobs in jeopardy in Moncton alone.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Environmental activist David Suzuki has come out in support of Dion's plan, saying "To oppose [the carbon tax plan], it's just nonsense.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] It's certainly the way we got to go" and giving an interview explaining why it is the most effective way to solve the environmental crisis.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The NDP's plan for the environment has focused on emissions trading, claiming their system will decrease greenhouse emissions by 80% by 2050.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The plan includes a series of financial incentives to retrofit public transit systems and transition the economy to be "green-collar".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The plan would also halt new oil sands development until emissions have been capped.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton has also criticized the Liberal carbon tax plan, stating it taxes families instead of polluters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Danny Williams, the Progressive Conservative premier of Newfoundland and Labrador, launched a campaign called Anything But Conservative, primarily targeted at Harper and the federal Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] He opposes a Conservative majority, due in part to Harper's promise during the 2006 election to modify the equalization formula to fully share offshore oil revenues with the province, which Williams says Harper has broken, and what Harper has stated he will do with a majority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Accordingly, all but one member of the provincial PC caucus supported not voting Conservative in this election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Power has also said his party's best hope of winning a seat in the province is in the riding of Avalon with incumbent candidate Fabian Manning.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Manning was defeated by Liberal Scott Andrews, while St.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] John's South—Mount Pearl, which were represented by Conservatives not running for re-election, were won by the NDP and Liberals, respectively, leaving the Conservatives with no representatives in Newfoundland and Labrador.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Since before the election was announced, the Conservative party ran attack ads about Dion, saying he was not a capable leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion criticized the Conservatives for running the ads.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In the footage Dion repeatedly failed to understand the conditional perfect construction used by the interviewer in a single repeatedly asked question.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The footage shows interviewer Steve Murphy asking Dion the question: "If you were the Prime Minister now, what would you have done about the economy, and this crisis, that Mr.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion had difficulty in understanding the question, repeatedly asking Murphy to clarify if he meant if Dion was Prime Minister now, next Tuesday on election day, last week, last month, 60 weeks ago, or two and a half years ago.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Eventually, after three start overs to the interview, Dion responded with what he would do if elected Prime Minister in the future.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] CTV initially agreed to restart the interviews and not air the false starts but changed their minds and announced that they felt it was their responsibility to show it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper responded to the clips by saying that "When you're running a trillion-and-a-half-dollar economy you don't get a chance to have do-overs, over and over again" and "What this incident actually indicates very clearly is Mr.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion and the Liberal Party really don't know what they would do on the economy", and when told that the difficulties were in part due to English being Dion's second language, Harper said: "I don't think this is a question of language at all.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Mark Dunn, a spokesman for Dion, accused the Tories of making fun of the Liberal leader's hearing issues.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dion responded to Harper's comments, saying Harper had "no class", saying "I did not understand the question", and "Maybe it's because I have a hearing problem, maybe because [English is] my second language, but I did not understand the question".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Both the Conservatives and the CTV have come under criticism for their handling of the footage, but they have stated they stand by their actions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Duceppe has called Harper's comments a "double standard", saying that many English-speaking politicians have little or no ability to speak French, yet francophones are somehow always expected to be perfect, and that the attack was an attempted "low blow".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] But Duceppe also took the opportunity to criticise Dion, suggesting he understood the question.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] "The real question is that I think Dion understood the question.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The real problem wasn't the language, it was the substance," Duceppe said, "He had nothing to say".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Layton also defended Dion, saying he has "struggled with questions, too".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Former Prime Minister Jean Chrétien has come out criticizing Harper's leadership abilities, noting especially Harper's controlling ways with his cabinet ministers, saying he would have quit if former prime minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau had treated him that way, that "Mr.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Former Prime Minister Paul Martin has also supported Dion's plans and abilities, and many have noted Dion's ability to get both Chrétien and Martin to support him, despite Chrétien and Martin's ongoing feud.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Minister of Agriculture Gerry Ritz, who has already been criticized by Canada's food scientists for his handling of the 2008 listeriosis outbreak, has also been criticized for making inappropriate comments, further angering the families of those affected.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Ritz had joked about the outbreak while he was on a conference call with scientists and political staffers on August 30, saying the political fallout from the outbreak was "like a death by a thousand cuts, or should I say cold cuts".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] In addition, when he was informed of a listeriosis-related death in Prince Edward Island, he quipped: "Please tell me it's [Liberal agriculture critic] Wayne Easter".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Despite calls for Ritz's resignation from the other parties and the public, Stephen Harper has supported Ritz and rebuffed calls for his resignation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Public Service Alliance of Canada revealed to the media that the Conservative party plans to cut federal funding to meat inspection programs by $3 million, effectively ending their operation in Manitoba, Saskatchewan and British Columbia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Canadian Alliance staff member and former Fraser Institute policy analyst, Owen Lippert, who wrote that speech was working on the current election campaign at Conservative campaign headquarters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On September 30, 2008, he issued a statement and resigned as a result of the incident.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On October 3, there was a second plagiarism allegation from the Liberals, who said that Harper had copied several sentences from a speech by former Ontario premier Mike Harris.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] Harper denied the allegation, saying "we're talking about a couple of sentences of fairly standard political rhetoric".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] On October 6, the Conservatives contended that Dion had also committed plagiarism when, as Minister of the Environment in 2005, he went to a United Nations conference on climate change to deliver a speech which had substantial similarities to the executive summary of a year old UN report.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberal party did not respond to the plagiarism allegation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In Quebec City, several ballot boxes containing votes from advance polls disappeared after the close of advance polling on October 7.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The boxes were stored in a closet at the home of a deputy returning officer.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Although there was no tampering of the boxes or the votes, three deputy returning officers were fired.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Deputy returning officers are the only polling officials allowed to handle ballots during the vote count and the law did allow for them to store the sealed boxes as may be necessary in large remote rural ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] However the boxes were returned a day late after the riding returning officer ordered their return.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] A number of political leaders and popular websites supported strategic voting in the election, mostly against the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The reasons varied from regional, such as Newfoundland and Labrador premier Danny Williams and his "Anything But Conservative" campaign, to ideological.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] If the Conservative candidate had little chance of winning the riding or was strongly entrenched, the site recommended "vote with your heart".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Similarly, a vote swapping organization on Facebook entitled "Anti-Harper Vote Swap Canada" also gained press.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The premise of that organization is that eligible voters in different electoral districts may exchange their votes, so that an opponent of a Conservative candidate in each district might have a better chance of being elected in that district.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Elections Canada deemed the practice legal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Green Party leader Elizabeth May sent out mixed signals about strategic voting.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 12, she recommended that in close ridings, supporters of green policies should consider voting for the NDP or Liberals to defeat the Conservatives, but on the same day she said: "I do not support strategic voting and I have not advised voters to choose any candidate other than Green".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In addition, during the final days of the campaign the Liberals attempted to attract strategic NDP and Green votes to stop the Conservatives, and the Conservatives attempted to attract Bloc votes to stop the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some students, homeless, and transient voters were turned away at the polls when they were unable to provide identification showing or otherwise confirming a place of residence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Legislation introduced in 2007 requires all voters to show one or two pieces of identification which confirm the voter's name and address, or to be vouched for by another voter who is able to show such identification.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Voter turnout at 58.8% was the lowest in Canadian federal election history, and the only time it has ever dipped below the 60% threshold.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] All federally funded parties except for the Greens attracted fewer total votes than in 2006; the Greens received nearly 280,000 more votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some voters were at first turned away because of failure to meet new and stricter proof of address requirements, including 2/3 of those attempting to vote at Dalhousie University, for example.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The effect this may have had on voter turnout is unknown.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In a federal election, a judicial recount is automatically ordered in a riding where the margin of victory is less than 0.1% (one one-thousandth) of the votes cast.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In cases where there is a larger but still narrow margin of victory, an elector can request a judicial recount.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Judicial recounts were ordered in six ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In one case, Brossard—La Prairie, the judicial recount overturned the reported victor, giving the seat to the Liberals' Alexandra Mendès instead of the Bloc incumbent Marcel Lussier.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In four other ridings, the recount confirmed the election results, although Liberal Ujjal Dosanjh's margin in Vancouver South was reduced from 33 votes to just 20.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] This was the slimmest victory of any riding in the entire election, until the results of the Kitchener-Waterloo recount reduced Peter Braid's margin of victory to a mere 17 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Dosanjh's Conservative opponent, Wai Young, appealed the recount to the Supreme Court of British Columbia, citing that not all of the ballot boxes were fully recounted.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] All ballots were eventually counted by November 4, confirming Dosanjh's victory by 20 votes, after the initial partial recount indicated a margin of 22 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] In a sixth riding, the recount was cancelled when the elector who had requested it withdrew the request.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Chris Reid, the Conservative candidate from Toronto Centre, resigned over controversial statements on his blog, which advocated revising Canadian gun control legislation to legalize concealed carriage of handguns.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Conservatives apologized after an aide to Pontiac candidate Lawrence Cannon told Aboriginal protesters that they were free to meet with Cannon "if you behave and you're sober and there's no problems and if you don't do a sit down and whatever".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Liberal candidate Simon Bédard was also asked to resign after he reiterated his 1990 comments, suggesting that lethal force should have been used in the Oka Crisis.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Liberal candidate Lesley Hughes was dropped by the Liberal Party after making controversial comments about the September 11, 2001 attacks.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] She continued to campaign as an independent, though she appeared as a Liberal on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Andrew McKeever, an NDP candidate in Durham, announced on October 3 that he would resign from the election campaign after it was revealed that he had posted comments on Facebook in which he called one war activist a "fascist bitch" and threatened to beat up another person.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] McKeever wrote comments peppered with expletives and calling the operators of a war resister website "Nazis".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] McKeever was also quoted as saying "I like the part in *Schindler's List* when the guard starts waxing the prisoners." McKeever's decision to drop out of the race came with just over a week left in the campaign, meaning his name would remain on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] One week before the publication of McKeever's resignation, NDP leader Jack Layton defended McKeever and refused to make him step down.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Julian West, the candidate for the riding of Saanich—Gulf Islands, dropped out of the race after details surfaced about an environmental event he attended 12 years ago when he went skinny-dipping and asked two teenagers to body-paint him.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Two other candidates in British Columbia who were proponents of marijuana decriminalization — Dana Larsen and Kirk Tousaw — resigned earlier after videos they had produced for Internet site Pot-TV were released to the media.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] One of the videos, filmed in 2000, showed Mr.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Larsen, former leader of the BC Marijuana Party, preparing to light up a joint before driving a car, after having taken the short-acting hallucinogenic drug DMT earlier in the evening.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] He was replaced by Liz Walker as the Green Party candidate, but remained on the ballot as an independent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] At an all-candidates debate staged for a high school student audience in Sudbury on September 29, independent candidate David Popescu responded to a question about same-sex marriage by stating that "homosexuals should be executed".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] His remarks were widely criticized across Canada, and the Greater Sudbury Police Service announced an investigation into whether the comments constituted a crime under Canadian hate speech legislation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] He was subsequently investigated by the Toronto Police as well, after a radio interview on October 2 in which he specifically advocated the execution of Egale Canada executive director Helen Kennedy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Supporters of Ontario Liberal MPs Carolyn Bennett (St.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Paul's) and Gerard Kennedy (Parkdale—High Park) who had Liberal signs outside their houses were subject to vandalism during the later hours of October 3, including graffiti, phone and cable lines being cut, and damage to vehicles that included brake cutting.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Toronto police reported over 30 incidents of vandalism as of October 6.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some of the victims did not realize their brakes had been cut until they were in traffic, and there was at least one near-accident.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Liberal Senator Jerry Grafstein was one of the residents who reported vandalism to his car.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Vandalism was also reported at the campaign offices of Trinity—Spadina Liberal candidate Christine Innes and Beaches—East York New Democratic Party candidate Marilyn Churley, as well as in Niagara Falls.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] After the election was called, Democracy Watch, an Ottawa-based advocacy group, filed a legal suit claiming that the election call was illegal because it violated the 2007 amendments to the Canada Elections Act.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] These amendments, introduced by the Harper government, set fixed dates for elections, and fulfilled a 2006 promise made by Harper to end the Prime Minister's ability to call snap elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 17, 2009, the Federal Court of Canada ruled that the election was not unfair, and therefore not illegal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Democracy Watch's appeal to the Federal Court of Appeal was also dismissed, and the Supreme Court denied leave to hear a further appeal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] The following is a list of ridings which had narrowly been lost by the indicated party in the 2006 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] For instance, under the Liberal column are the 15 seats in which they came closest to winning but did not.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Listed is the name of the riding, followed by the party which was victorious (in parentheses) and the margin, in terms of percentage of the vote, by which the party lost.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] These ridings were targeted by the specified party because the party had lost them by a very slim margin in the 2006 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Up to 15 are shown, with a maximum margin of victory of 15%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Combined, the three opposition parties constitute a majority of seats in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Parliament was due to vote on a no-confidence motion on December 8; if successful, the Liberals and NDP would have formally asked the Governor General to form a coalition minority government for 30 months, while the BQ pledged to support for at least 18 months.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Liberal leader Stéphane Dion would have become prime minister until the selection of his successor at the Liberal leadership convention in May 2009, and a coalition cabinet would have comprised 18 Liberal (including a finance minister) and 6 NDP ministers.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Governor General Michaëlle Jean had cut short a state visit to Europe "in light of the current political situation in Canada".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] On December 4, 2008, Jean granted Harper's request to prorogue Parliament until January 26, 2009, thereby staving off the prospect of an imminent change in government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p02] Dion stood down as Liberal leader on December 10 and was replaced by interim leader Michael Ignatieff, who would later be elected unopposed as permanent leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p03] Ujjal Dosanjh was previously an NDP member of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia, and was Premier of British Columbia until 2001.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p03] Gail Shea was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p03] Keith Milligan was previously a member of the Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island, as well as Premier of Prince Edward Island for a short time in 1996.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p03] Nancy Charest was previously a member of the National Assembly of Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p04] By-elections in progress in four vacant ridings were cancelled when the general election was called.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p04] Student votes are mock elections that run parallel to actual elections, in which students not of voting age participate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p04] They are administered by Student Vote Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p04] Student vote elections are for educational purposes and do not count towards the results.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2008-canadian-federal-election-p04] Though there were 308 ridings, only 289 were declared.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The **2011 Canadian federal election** was held on May 2, 2011, to elect members to the House of Commons of Canada of the 41st Canadian Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The writs of election for the 2011 election were issued by Governor General David Johnston on March 26.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Prime Minister Stephen Harper advised the Governor General to dissolve parliament after the House of Commons passed a motion of non-confidence against the government, finding it to be in contempt of Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A few days before, the three opposition parties had rejected the minority government's proposed budget.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Conservative Party remained in power, increasing its seat count from a minority to a majority government, marking the first election since 1988 that a right-of-centre party formed a majority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal Party, sometimes dubbed the "natural governing party", was reduced to third party status for the first time as they won the fewest seats in its history, and party leader Michael Ignatieff was defeated in his riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois lost official party status for the first time since contesting general elections in 1993.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Party leader Gilles Duceppe was defeated in his riding and subsequently resigned as leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party led by Jack Layton won the largest number of seats in its history, enabling it to form the Official Opposition for the first time in the party's history, as they made a major breakthrough in Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Green Party elected its first member to the House of Commons with its leader, Elizabeth May, becoming MP for Saanich—Gulf Islands.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The 2008 federal election resulted in the continuation of the incumbent Conservative minority government, headed by Stephen Harper.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The 40th Parliament was marked by two controversial prorogations: the first in December 2008 which ended an attempted opposition coalition, and the second a year following, which prompted public protests.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Following the first prorogation, Michael Ignatieff and the Liberal Party provided support for the government of Prime Minister Stephen Harper.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On August 31, 2009, the Liberals withdrew their backing but the NDP under Jack Layton abstained and the Conservatives survived the confidence motion.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff's attempt to force a September 2009 election was reported as a miscalculation, as polls showed that most Canadians did not want another election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff's popularity as well as that of the Liberals dropped off considerably immediately afterwards.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In 2011, Elections Canada laid charges against the Conservative Party, alleging contraventions of the Canada Elections Act five years earlier.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Milliken directed both matters to committee and set as the deadline for its report March 21, 2011, one day before the budget was to be tabled.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The committee found the government to be in contempt of Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The vote divided along party lines, with the governing but minority Conservative members of Parliament (MPs) opposing the finding and issuing a dissenting report.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A cabinet being found in contempt of parliament was without precedent in Canada or any other Commonwealth country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Earlier that week, all three opposition parties had indicated that they would oppose the government's budget; the NDP said that the concessions that the Conservatives made did not go far enough.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A number of controversies took place during the election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The English- and French-language debates took place on April 12 and 13 respectively.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Therefore, the Green Party was excluded, despite earning 6.8 per cent of the popular vote in the 2008 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On March 30, Stephen Harper challenged Michael Ignatieff to a one-on-one televised debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Although Ignatieff accepted the challenge, this was opposed by the other opposition parties.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The idea was later rejected by the broadcast consortium and cancelled.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On April 1, comedian Rick Mercer suggested over Twitter hosting a one-on-one debate between Stephen Harper and Michael Ignatieff at Toronto's Massey Hall.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] He later added he would donate $50,000 to the charities of their choosing if they were willing to participate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff immediately accepted the challenge and named the Alzheimer Society as his charity of choice, as his mother succumbed to Alzheimer's disease in 1992.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Harper did not respond to the challenge.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In an interview with *The Globe and Mail* published on April 1, Troy Reeb, the broadcast consortium chairman, discussed the process behind setting up the leaders' debates and the rationale for various decisions made, including the decision to exclude the Green Party's leader Elizabeth May.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On April 5, the Federal Court rejected the Green Party's request for an expedited hearing on the matter prior to the scheduled debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On April 10, the date of the French leaders debate was changed from April 14 to 13 due to worries of broadcasting conflicts with the NHL playoffs scheduled for April 14.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Also on April 10, Elizabeth May participated in a panel interview on CHCH-TV in Hamilton, which she was invited to attend, as were the leaders of the Bloc, Liberals, New Democrats and Conservatives, by Channel Zero, whose president was disappointed by May's exclusion from the leaders' debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A joint press conference and public forum was staged by 11 of the 18 registered parties and one unregistered party on April 23, 2011, at York University.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Forum organizers invited the leaders from all registered political parties who do not have seats in parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Parties were able to explain their platforms and responded to questions from the audience.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] As a forum, the goal was an inter-party discussion of major issues, however some debate did occur.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Participants in the forum were the Animal Alliance Environmental Voters, the Canadian Action Party, the Christian Heritage Party, the Communist Party, the First Peoples National, the Libertarian Party, the Marijuana Party, the Marxist–Leninist Party, the Rhinoceros Party, and the Pirate Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Green Party leader Elizabeth May refused to participate in the forum claiming they are not one of "the small, fringe parties".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In the week before the leaders debate, on April 8, a poll showed the New Democratic Party (NDP) support at 13.2%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A reversal of fortune began on April 16, when an Angus Reid poll indicated a tie in support for the NDP and the Liberals, both polling at 25%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The New Democrats' poll numbers then moved significantly ahead of the Liberals and slightly or moderately behind the Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The surge began in Quebec, with the NDP surprising many observers by surpassing the previously front-running Bloc in Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In the entirety of Canada, the NDP surged past the Liberals to take the second place behind the Conservatives; in Quebec, the NDP took first place.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The NDP surge became the dominant narrative of the last week of the campaign, as other parties turned their attacks on the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ruth Ellen Brosseau, the NDP candidate in Berthier—Maskinongé, won despite not running a campaign, barely speaking French at this time and being on holiday in Las Vegas at the time of the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The NDP's rise in popularity was nicknamed **Orange Crush**, an allusion to the soft drink with the same name and the party's colour.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] It was also nicknamed the **Orange Wave**.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Pre-campaign, there are no limits to what a political party, candidate, or third party can spend — spending rules are only in force once the writ is dropped and the campaign has officially begun.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Most major newspapers endorsed the Conservatives, and none solely endorsed the Liberals or Greens.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Canada's highest circulated newspaper, the *Toronto Star*, endorsed the NDP but also advised readers to vote against the Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] was nominated as a Liberal, but lost party support after being nominated, and continued to run as an independent; he is listed here as a Liberal rather than an independent, as he was listed as a Liberal on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] failed to run candidates in the 2011 election and was deregistered by Elections Canada on April 13, 2011.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] With an overall voter turnout of 61.4% and 14,823,408 ballots cast, the Conservative Party remained in power, moving from a minority to a majority government by winning 166 of the 308 seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party won the largest number of seats in their history, including a large majority of seats in Quebec (where they had previously only ever elected two candidates) and formed the Official Opposition for the first time.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal Party won the fewest seats in their history and party leader Michael Ignatieff was defeated in his own riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois, which had always won at least a majority of seats in Quebec in every election of their existence, lost nearly all their seats, and thus also their official party status, including the seat of their leader Gilles Duceppe.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Green Party leader Elizabeth May became the first Member of Parliament elected to represent the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada ordered three judicial recounts, and an elector initiated a fourth.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff announced on May 3, 2011, that he would step down as leader of the Liberal Party when it chose his successor.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff took a teaching position at the University of Toronto after his defeat in Etobicoke—Lakeshore.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] He decided to teach classes in the law faculty, the department of political science, the Munk School of Global Affairs and the School of Public Policy and Governance.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Ignatieff stated that, "The life that I like the best is teaching.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] It's the end of my life as a politician".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Bob Rae, Liberal MP for Toronto Centre and former Premier of Ontario (1990 to 1995, as a New Democrat), subsequently became interim leader of the Liberal Party, with a Liberal leadership election which took place April 14, 2013, during which Justin Trudeau was chosen as leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Duceppe resigned as Bloc Québécois leader on election night following his defeat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Louis Plamondon, MP for Bas-Richelieu—Nicolet—Bécancour and Dean of the House, subsequently became interim parliamentary leader of the Bloc.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Former MP Daniel Paillé, who lost his seat in the election, won the Bloc leadership election to succeed Duceppe on December 11, 2011.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On July 25, 2011, Jack Layton took a leave of absence to fight a newly diagnosed cancer.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Nycole Turmel, former union leader and newly elected MP for Hull—Aylmer, was named interim leader of the New Democratic Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] A leadership election was held on March 24, 2012, and Tom Mulcair was elected leader of the New Democratic Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The losing parties in the Berthier—Maskinongé riding claimed that the nomination papers for Ruth Ellen Brosseau, the newly elected NDP Member of Parliament for the riding, had irregularities.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada has insisted that Brosseau's nomination papers were legitimate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada stated that "The decision to overturn or uphold the results is at the discretion of the courts and not Elections Canada".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal Party of Canada attracted controversy regarding the past racist comments and White supremacist history of one of its candidates in northern Quebec, Andre Forbes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] His history as a white supremacist activist and past hate speech against Muslims, First Nations and LGBTQ+ people was uncovered by the NDP.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff immediately removed Forbes as a candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In early 2012, there were allegations of voter suppression during the election, starting the robocall scandal.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) investigated claims that robocalls were used in an attempt to dissuade voters from casting their ballot by telling them their poll stations had changed location.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] While the Elections Canada investigation initially focused on calls sent into Guelph amidst nationwide complaints, the investigation continued to expand in scope and to examine complaints in other ridings across the country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Reports of fraudulent automated or live calls targeting opposition supporters were published in 100 ridings and Elections Canada acknowledged it was investigating telephone election fraud complaints in 247 of Canada's 308 federal ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] On March 27, 2012, the Council of Canadians announced that they had launched a lawsuit in the Federal Court of Canada to ask for by-elections to be ordered in seven ridings where complaints were received and where Conservatives had won by slim margins.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The ridings named were Don Valley East, Winnipeg South Centre, Saskatoon-Rosetown-Biggar, Vancouver Island North, Yukon, Nipissing-Timiskaming and Elmwood-Transcona.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The case was heard over two weeks starting December 9, 2012.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Mosley ruled in May 2013 that fraud had occurred in Guelph and that voting irregularities and misconduct occurred in all six of the contested ridings, but that it was not significant enough to warrant overturning the election results.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The judge also ruled that the mostly likely source of the fraud was the Conservative Party of Canada's (using the CIMS database) and that there was no evidence that its use was approved by the CPC.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In April 2013, a criminal charge in the matter was laid on Michael Sona, a former Conservative staffer who was the communications officer and official Ottawa liaison for the Guelph Conservative campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In August 2014, he was convicted of the charge.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] They alleged there was a second, secret, illegal bank account containing $300,000.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] In the wake of the election, pundits widely believed in a theme of major political realignment.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] The *Economist* said, "the election represents the biggest realignment of Canadian politics since 1993." Lawrence Martin, commentator for *The Globe and Mail*, claimed that "Harper has completed a remarkable reconstruction of a Canadian political landscape that endured for more than a century.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Newman's *When the Gods Changed: The Death of Liberal Canada*, provocatively asserted that the Liberals had become an "endangered species" and that an NDP-led opposition would mean that "fortune favours the Harper government" in subsequent campaigns.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] However, the resurgence of the Liberal Party in the 2015 election has since challenged that narrative.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2011-canadian-federal-election] Though there were 308 ridings, only 301 were declared.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The **2015 Canadian federal election** was held on October 19, 2015, to elect the 338 members of the House of Commons of the 42nd Parliament of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In accordance with the maximum four-year term under a 2007 amendment to the *Canada Elections Act*, the writs of election for the 2015 election were issued by Governor General David Johnston on August 4.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] (In both cases, it was Pierre, Justin Trudeau’s father, who attempted in 1979 to win a 4th consecutive term and succeeded in 1980 in winning a fourth term overall.) This is also the most recent election in which a majority government was formed.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal Party won 184 seats, forming a majority government with its leader Justin Trudeau becoming prime minister.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Trudeau and the rest of his cabinet were sworn in on November 4, 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Conservative Party, led by incumbent Prime Minister Stephen Harper, won 99 seats, becoming the Official Opposition after nearly a decade on the government benches.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party, led by Tom Mulcair, won 44 seats, becoming the third-largest party in the House of Commons, after having formed the Official Opposition following the 2011 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois won 10 seats, the Green Party won 1 seat, and Strength in Democracy lost all its seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal Party's increase of 148 seats from the previous election was the largest-ever numerical increase by a party in a Canadian election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Prior to the campaign, the Liberals had held only 36 seats—the fewest seats ever held at dissolution by any federal party that won the following election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] It was the second largest number of seats won in a federal election for the Liberals, the best being 191 in 1949.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] This was the first election since 2000 in which the Liberals gained seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] It was also the first election since 1980 in which the Liberals won the most seats in Quebec, and the first election since 1968 in which the Liberals won the most seats in British Columbia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The election also had the highest voter turnout since 1993.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Every party represented in the House of Commons except the Liberal Party recorded a decrease in its popular vote share.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] There was an increase in voter turnout among all age groups.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The largest was among eligible voters aged 18 to 24, which increased 18.3 points, to 57.1%.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada reported that this was the biggest increase in turnout among this age group since it began making demographic turnout estimates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Following the election, Harper conceded defeat to Trudeau and resigned as leader of the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Gilles Duceppe resigned as leader of the Bloc Québécois shortly after the election on October 22, 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Tom Mulcair announced his intention to remain leader of the NDP, but was forced to step down in October 2017, after losing a party vote on his leadership in the spring of 2016.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The 2011 federal election resulted in the continuation of the incumbent Conservative government headed by Stephen Harper, while the New Democratic Party (NDP) became Official Opposition and the Liberal Party became the third party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois won four seats and the Green Party won one seat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff and Bloc leader Gilles Duceppe resigned shortly after failing to win their own ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois lost official party status by failing to attain the minimum seats needed (12).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Bob Rae was chosen as interim leader of the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In July 2011 Jack Layton, suffering from cancer, temporarily stepped down as leader of the NDP because of illness, indicating his intention to return for the reconvening of Parliament in September.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Weeks later Layton died of cancer and was given a state funeral.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In March 2012 Tom Mulcair was elected leader of the New Democratic Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In April 2013 Justin Trudeau was elected leader of the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Bloc Québécois leader Daniel Paillé stepped down in December 2013 and was eventually replaced in June 2014 by Mario Beaulieu, who in turn was replaced by Duceppe in June 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In late 2014, MPs Jean-François Larose of the NDP and Jean-François Fortin of the Bloc formed the new political party Strength in Democracy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] As set forth in the *Fair Representation Act*, the number of seats in the House of Commons to be contested in the 42nd Canadian federal election was 338, an increase of 30 seats from the 308 seats comprising the House of Commons of Canada of the 41st Parliament of Canada, at its dissolution.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Prime Minister Stephen Harper requested writs of election for a federal general election from Governor General David Johnston on August 2.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The official proclamations were issued on August 4.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The date of the vote is determined by the fixed-date Canada Elections Act.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] At 11 weeks, the campaign was the longest in modern Canadian history.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] As a result of the 2012 federal electoral redistribution, the number of electoral districts was increased to 338, with additional seats based on population assigned to Alberta (6), British Columbia (6), Ontario (15), and Quebec (3).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] 61 MPs chose to not seek reelection at the 2015 federal election, meaning they were Members of Parliament (MPs) in the 41st Parliament of Canada, but chose not to stand for election to the 42nd Parliament of Canada (in some cases after being deselected by their parties).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Traditionally, party leaders participated in at least two nationally televised debates during the federal election – at least one each in English and French.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] These debates were produced by a consortium of Canada's major television networks.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In May 2015, the Conservatives said they would not participate in the consortium debates and instead would take part in as many as five independently staged debates in the run-up to the fall federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Ultimately, the Conservatives agreed to participate in a French-language debate organized by the consortium of broadcasters as one of their five debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party confirmed that Tom Mulcair would accept every debate where the prime minister was present.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The NDP had previously confirmed its intention to participate in both of the consortium debates before Stephen Harper withdrew but ultimately only participated in the French language consortium debate which included the Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Liberal leader Justin Trudeau attended the *Maclean's*, *Globe and Mail*, and French consortium debates; and the Liberals confirmed he would attend the other debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois attended the French language consortium debate and confirmed its attendance at the French-language TVA debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Green Party attended the *Maclean's* and French language consortium debates, and confirmed its intention to participate in the English language consortium debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Strength in Democracy, which had the same number of seats in the House of Commons at dissolution as the Greens and Bloc Québécois, were not invited to participate in any of the televised debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The leaders of the party objected to their exclusion and launched a petition demanding that all parties represented in Parliament be invited to the debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Other minor parties without representation in the House of Commons were not invited to participate in any of the televised debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The second Canadian federal election to significantly incorporate social media, the 2015 campaign was notable for the rise of new avenues of scrutiny for potential candidates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] A number of damaging revelations for each of the major political parties late in the campaign led to calls for increased vetting amongst political strategists, academics and outside observers.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Evolution of voting intentions during the campaign leading up to the 2015 Canadian federal election to be held on October 19, 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Points represent results of individual polls.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Before the campaign, there were no limits to what a political party, candidate, or third party (corporations, unions, special interest groups, etc.) can spend: spending rules are only in force after the writs have been dropped and the campaign has begun.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Because the election period is set longer than the standard 37-day election period, spending limits are increased in proportion to the length of the period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Political parties receive a reimbursement for 50 per cent of their election expenses during the writ period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Similarly, candidates (through their official agents) receive a reimbursement of 60 per cent of their election expenses during the writ period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Both reimbursements are publicly funded.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Elections Canada reports that during the financial quarter preceding the writ period, the Conservatives received $7.4 million in contributions, the NDP received $4.5 million, and the Liberals received $4.0 million.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The NDP had the most individual donors at 48,314, followed by the Conservatives at 45,532 and then the Liberals at 32,789.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party stated that it collected greater than $9 million in the third quarter of 2015, the most it ever received from donors, and greater than the quarterly record established by the Conservative Party in 2011.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Individuals are able to give up to $1,500 to each political party and an additional $1,500 to all the registered associations, nomination contestants and candidates of each registered party combined.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] A person or group must register as a third party immediately after incurring election advertising expenses totalling $500 or more.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] There are strict limits on advertising expenses, and specific limits that can be incurred to promote or oppose the election of one or more candidates in a particular electoral district.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] There were 112 registered third parties in the 2015 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] There was a $150,000 election advertising expenses limit.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Of that amount, no more than $8,788 could be incurred to promote or oppose the election of one or more candidates in a particular electoral district.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The 2015 CES included two survey components.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Both included two waves of questions, one in the campaign period (CPS) and a recontact wave after the election (PES).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The non-probability online survey included a sample of Canadians from across the country (CPS n=11,614; PES n=6,554).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The following table is the indicated vote choice in the 2015 election, cross-tabbed with demographic questions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The weights have been adjusted to match the actual results of the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Student votes are mock elections, running parallel to actual elections, in which students not of voting age participate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Student vote elections are administered by Student Vote Canada, and are for educational purposes and do not count towards the results.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Note that the total seats adds up to 340 instead of 338, due to ties.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Hours after conceding defeat on election night, incumbent Prime Minister Stephen Harper resigned as leader of the Conservative Party, though he announced his intention to remain in the new parliament as a backbencher after being elected in the riding of Calgary Heritage.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The Conservative caucus met on November 5, 2015, and elected former health minister and Alberta MP Rona Ambrose as interim leader of the party, and hence, interim Leader of the Official Opposition.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] The next Conservative Party of Canada leadership election was held on May 27, 2017.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Following his swearing in on November 4, 2015, Prime Minister Justin Trudeau announced that parliament would reconvene on December 3, 2015, with the Speech from the Throne to follow on December 4.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] In the aftermath of the 2011 election, many pundits had characterized it as a realigning election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Lawrence Martin, commentator for *The Globe and Mail* said, "Harper has completed a remarkable reconstruction of a Canadian political landscape that endured for more than a century.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Despite the grim outlook and poor early poll numbers, when the 2015 election was held, the Liberals under Trudeau made an unprecedented comeback.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Gaining 148 seats, they won a majority government for the first time since 2000.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Chantal Hébert, writing in the *Toronto Star,* claimed the comeback was "headed straight for the history books" and that Harper's name would "forever be joined with that of his Liberal nemesis in Canada's electoral annals".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2015-canadian-federal-election] Spencer McKay, writing for the *National Post*, suggested that "maybe we've witnessed a revival of Canada's 'natural governing party'".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The **2019 Canadian federal election** was held on October 21, 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Members of the House of Commons were elected to the 43rd Canadian Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] In keeping with the maximum four-year term under a 2007 amendment to the *Canada Elections Act*, the writs of election for the 2019 election were issued by Governor General Julie Payette on September 11, 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] It was also the first time since 1979 that the party with the most votes overall did not win the most seats, and the first election since 1926 in which the Liberals won the most seats without receiving the most votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives, led by Andrew Scheer, won 121 seats and remained the Official Opposition.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Bloc Québécois, led by Yves-François Blanchet, won 32 seats to regain official party status and became the third party for the first time since 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The New Democratic Party, led by Jagmeet Singh, won 24 seats, its worst result since 2004.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Green Party, led by Elizabeth May, saw its best election results with three seats and for the first time received over one million votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Greens also elected their first MP outside of British Columbia, Jenica Atwin in Fredericton, New Brunswick.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Independent MP Jody Wilson-Raybould won her seat and was the first independent to win a seat in over a decade.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] In their first election, the People's Party failed to win any seats, as leader Maxime Bernier lost his own seat in Beauce, a seat he won as a Conservative in the previous four elections before forming his own party following his unsuccessful bid for the Conservative Party's leadership.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The 2015 federal election resulted in a Liberal majority government headed by Justin Trudeau.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives became the Official Opposition (with Stephen Harper announcing his resignation as party leader) and the New Democrats (NDP) became the third party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] While members of the Bloc Québécois and the Greens were elected to the House, both failed to achieve the required number of MPs—twelve—for official party status.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bloc leader Gilles Duceppe announced his resignation shortly after the election, and was succeeded by Parti Québécois MNA Martine Ouellet.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] After losing a leadership review, Ouellet announced she would step down as Bloc leader on June 11, 2018, and was succeeded by Yves-François Blanchet on January 17, 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Tom Mulcair was rejected as NDP party leader; he gained only 48% of the vote at the NDP's April 2016 leadership review.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The party held a leadership election on October 1, 2017, electing Ontario MPP and the former Deputy Leader of the Ontario New Democratic Party Jagmeet Singh as Mulcair's successor.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The table below lists parties represented in the House of Commons after the 2015 federal election, and the standings at dissolution.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bill C-44 was passed in 2017 and assigned responsibility to the Parliamentary Budget Office to calculate the cost of party platforms for elections; the review was available in the 2019 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Parliamentary Budget Office had a $500,000 budget for costing party platforms for this election, but announced it would only review a party platform at the request of the authoring party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] It also conducted confidential assessments of independent and party platform proposals preceding the election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The service was also available to members of parliament representing a party without official party status in the House of Commons, like Elizabeth May's Green Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] In the lead-up to the 2015 federal election, Trudeau committed to replacing first-past-the-post voting, but the first-past-the-post electoral system was ultimately retained.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Following the Liberal victory, the Special Committee on Electoral Reform was formed, and in December 2016 recommended a proportional electoral system be introduced following a national referendum.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The report was criticized by Minister of Democratic Institutions Maryam Monsef for not recommending a specific electoral system, though the committee argued that it had fulfilled its mandate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] When only completed, realized pledges were calculated, Harper's government, in their last year, kept 77 per cent of promises while the Liberal government kept 53.5 per cent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The book notes that Harper's pledges tended towards transactional pledges which target sub-populations while Trudeau's government's promises were transformative—ambitious pledges the Liberals took while they were the third-place party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] According to Elections Canada rules, third parties are allowed to spend $1,023,400 in the pre-election period between June 30 and the start of the election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] They can spend an additional $511,700 during the election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Similarly, electoral district associations receive a reimbursement of 60 per cent of their election expenses during the writ period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] A person or group must register as a third party immediately after incurring expenses totaling $500 or more on regulated activities that take place during the pre-election period or election period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] The regulated activities are partisan activities (that promote parties or candidates), election surveys, partisan advertising and election advertising.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] One cannot spend money or use their resources to influence Canadian elections if they are a foreign third party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] There are also strict limits on expenses related to regulated activities, and specific limits that can be incurred to promote or oppose the election of one or more candidates in a particular electoral district.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Registered third parties are subject to an election advertising expenses limit of $1,023,400 in the pre-election period, of which $10,234 can be spent in a given electoral district and $511,700 during the election period.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p01] Of that amount, no more than $4,386 can be spent to promote or oppose the election of one or more candidates in a particular electoral district.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Parliament of Canada's Ethics Commissioner, Mario Dion, found that Trudeau improperly influenced then Minister of Justice and Attorney General Jody Wilson-Raybould to intervene in an ongoing criminal case against Quebec-based construction company SNC-Lavalin.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Trudeau government has maintained that there was no undue pressure or law broken, that offering SNC-Lavalin a deferred prosecution agreement (DPA) could save jobs, and that the controversy resulted from a misunderstanding and an "erosion of trust".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The affair became public in February 2019, shortly after Wilson-Raybould had been shuffled to another cabinet position.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Wilson-Raybould resigned from cabinet later that day.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] This was followed by the resignation of cabinet minister Jane Philpott, over the government's handling of the affair.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In April, Wilson-Raybould and Philpott were expelled by Trudeau from the Liberal caucus; Trudeau cited concerns for division in and subsequent weakening of the Liberal party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On April 2, 2019, Wilson-Raybould, as Liberal candidate for Vancouver Granville, and Philpott, as Liberal candidate for Markham—Stouffville, were deselected as candidates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In late August, Party deputy leader Ralph Goodale, Liberal candidate for Regina—Wascana, Lawrence MacAulay, candidate for Cardigan, and Francis Scarpaleggia, candidate for Lac-Saint-Louis, were singled out for their opposition to same-sex marriage.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Pundits argued that Goodale was being hypocritical, due to his role with Scheer and the same-sex marriage incident.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Goodale later stated that he had evolved on the position and wanted answers from Scheer.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 30, Hassan Guillet, Liberal candidate for Saint-Léonard—Saint-Michel, was dropped as a candidate following allegations of anti-Semitic comments from B'nai B'rith.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Guillet's nomination previously raised concern that his ethnicity would be out of place in the majority Italian riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Guillet denied the allegation, alleged that the Liberals were aware of the post, and that they "imposed" his replacement Patricia Lattanzio, on the riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 20, Guillet announced he would run as an independent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Sameer Zuberi, Liberal candidate for Pierrefonds—Dollard, was nominated on September 15, despite questioning Osama bin Laden's involvement in 9/11 in a social media post.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Zuberi called the accusations false saying it was an attempt by the Conservatives to deflect attention away from their own candidates with extremist or white supremacist leanings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 18, *L'Express of Drummondville* reported that the Liberal candidate for Drummond, William Morales' nomination victory was attended by two convicted criminals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Morales said that while he maintains contact with Spanish-speaking members from the Drummondville community the two people were not involved in his campaign and he does not have close relations with them.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He later told his local newspaper that he interacts with members regardless of their background.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 18, Trudeau attracted controversy for a photograph published in *Time* magazine, in which he wore brownface makeup to a party at West Point Grey Academy, where he was a teacher, in 2001.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Trudeau called it a mistake and apologized publicly for it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] When apologizing, Trudeau also confessed to having worn similar makeup in high-school.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Following his apology, an earlier instance from the early 1990s of Trudeau wearing blackface makeup was uncovered.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The following day, Trudeau apologized again and said he was "not that person anymore".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He also said that it should not be called "makeup" but blackface.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some commentators labelled this hypocritical, since the Liberals had exposed the past misdeeds of some Conservative candidates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Trudeau drew a mixed reaction from the public.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some were upset and contemplated changing their vote, while others defended him, such as members of minorities, minority community groups, racialized commentators and some of his opponents.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, Trudeau announced that he wanted to apologize personally to Jagmeet Singh, who replied that he would only meet Trudeau for an apology if it was "politics-free" and private.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Following the announcement, Singh received a call from Trudeau on September 24, and they talked privately for 15 to 20 minutes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In the days following the scandal, pollsters pointed out that the majority of Canadians either were not bothered by the scandal or had accepted Trudeau's apology.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 23, Del Arnold, Liberal candidate for Calgary Shepard, apologized to Conservative rival Tom Kmiec after spreading misleading information about his place of residence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Arnold has not apologized for a deleted tweet that accused Andrew Scheer of having links to "white supremacy" and the 2017 Unite the Right rally in Virginia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] She later apologized for her remarks, saying that "the comments I made on GBKM FM were insensitive," and further adding "I should have known better, and I apologize".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 13, due to a security threat, Trudeau appeared 90 minutes late to a campaign rally.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Trudeau took extraordinary security precautions at the event.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He wore a bulletproof vest and was surrounded by heavily armed security personnel.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] His wife was also supposed to introduce him, but she did not appear on stage.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Liberal Party did not reveal the nature of the threat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer and Singh both showed concern for Trudeau following the threat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The following day, the RCMP was still with the Liberal leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Furthermore, Trudeau explained that he followed advice from the RCMP and that this event will not change the way he campaigns.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 14, Trudeau dodged multiple questions about a possible coalition with the NDP in a minority scenario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He responded that he remains focused on winning a majority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] This worried CPC insiders and prompted the Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario to call an extended recess of the provincial legislature to reduce negative news coverage, in order to help the federal Tories.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] If the Conservatives lost the election, Scheer pledged to blame it on Ford during his leadership review.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Therefore, leading up to the campaign, Andrew Scheer distanced himself from Ford and later campaigned without him.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Meanwhile, the Liberals and Scheer's opponents tried to capitalize on Ford's unpopularity by linking Scheer to the Premier multiple times.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Several CPC candidates were dropped leading to and during the course of the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On April 25, Harzadan Khattra, the candidate for Dufferin—Caledon, was disqualified after a fellow contestant sent the party verifiable information about "membership buying, improper voting, and other concerns".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On June 28, Salim Mansur, the candidate for London North Centre, was disqualified over alleged fears that the Liberals would characterize Mansur's record as Islamophobic.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On July 10, Mark King, the candidate for Nipissing—Timiskaming, was stripped of his nomination for disputed reasons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 12, Cameron Ogilvie, Conservative candidate for Winnipeg North, resigned as a candidate after the party became aware of withheld social media post which the Conservative Party described as "discriminatory".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 4, the party announced that Heather Leung, the candidate for Burnaby North—Seymour, was dropped as reports surfaced of her making anti-LGBTQ comments in a video from 2011.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Due to the deadline for naming candidates having passed, her name remained on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] If she were to win, she would not sit in the party's caucus.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Questions were raised as to why it took the party so long to remove her, since she was "a known commodity" when she was nominated.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] She had made anti-LGBTQ and anti-abortion comments in the past and ignored the media for months.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Her riding association had also been criticized for their controversial social media posts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 10, Leung claimed she was misunderstood and that her comments were lost in translation since English is her third language.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] However, she did not apologize for her comments.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On July 10, Cyma Musarat, Conservative candidate for Pickering—Uxbridge, faced an allegation from fellow party members that she won her nomination by using improper voting procedures.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Conservative Party faced an accusation that its headquarters had been delaying the nomination contest to find a different candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] From July 24 to September 15, Ghada Melek attracted attention.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] This conservative candidate for Mississauga—Streetsville, was revealed by former organizers of the Ontario Progressive Conservative Party to have been rejected as a candidate in the provincial riding over Twitter posts about Muslim extremism.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] National Council of Canadian Muslims had issues over Melek's Twitter posts about Islam and LGBT+ community.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer accepted an apology she issued for her comments.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, CTV News obtained her provincial vetting report and her promotion of conspiracy theories was seen as another factor behind her disqualification.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] When asked about the provincial party red-flagging Melek, Scheer defended her again.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 22, Scheer faced questions over a 2005 online video in which he spoke against same-sex marriage Scheer himself did not respond until a press conference a week later where he argued that Trudeau was raising a wedge issue; Several pundits had an issue with his response.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Weeks later, Scheer was asked if he needed to apologize for his comments giving the standards he set for his candidates; however he gave no response.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] After Trudeau's apology regarding blackface, Scheer was asked again if he should apologize for his words; he gave no response.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer once again chose to not answer the question directly on popular Quebec talk show *Tout le monde en parle*.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He said that he supports the law and the rights of Canadians, but that he will not walk in Pride parades.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Between August 26 and 30, the Conservatives were questioned on abortion.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Alain Rayes, Scheer's Quebec lieutenant, attracted attention after he told a Quebec radio station that he misspoke on the party stance on abortion.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A few days later, Scheer held a press conference, where he addressed the issue.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] However, his answers were seen as confusing in the media, and anti-abortion activists found his answers to be mixed-messaging.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A day later, Scheer said that he and his cabinet would vote against anti-abortion bills if the debate is re-opened.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer reiterated this statement on *Tout le monde en parle.* A day after his rivals pushed him to clarify his position during the TVA debate, Scheer mentioned that he was pro-life but reiterated what he said in the past concerning anti-abortion bills.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 12, Rachel Wilson, Conservative candidate for York Centre, attracted attention after a video was posted online that called for pro-life legislation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Wilson did not comment when asked about abortion legislation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 13, Arpan Khanna, Conservative candidate for Brampton North, apologized after it was revealed that he offhandedly used the slur "fag" to tease a friend.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 14, Justina McCaffrey, Conservative candidate for Kanata—Carleton, attracted attention for making negative remarks in a video about Justin Trudeau and Francophones, and her relationship with Faith Goldy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] She departed a campaign event when confronted by reporters, but later released a statement apologizing for her comments and later stated that her relationship with Goldy ended a longtime ago.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] However, there were pictures of the two together in 2017—one of them featured Goldy doing the "OK sign".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Conservative campaign manager Hamish Marshall's past role as a director of Rebel Media was also questioned, since Goldy was an on-screen personality before being fired.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 7, the Canadian Press discovered that McCaffrey was a member of the controversial religious group Opus Dei.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The CPC's spokesperson responded by saying that they do not question their candidates about their personal religious beliefs.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 28, *The Globe and Mail* revealed that they found no record of Scheer receiving the licence required by law to work as an insurance agent or broker in Saskatchewan despite him claiming so in the past.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Robert Fife, the Ottawa bureau chief for *The Globe and Mail*, explained that Scheer was an insurance clerk.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer responded by saying that he did receive his accreditation, but that he left the insurance office before the licensing process was finalized.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, the Insurance Brokers Association of Saskatchewan said that Scheer completed just one of four required courses to become an insurance broker.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The IBAS declined to comment further and said that a formal complaint had been launched by Liberal MP Marco Mendicino to the General Insurance Council of Saskatchewan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 3, *The Globe and Mail* revealed that Scheer had dual Canadian and American citizenship.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The latter was obtained through his American-born father.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He began the process of renouncing his US citizenship in August.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer confirmed that he has filed US tax returns.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A party spokesperson added that he let his US passport lapse and that he has not voted in any U.S. election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The party verified that he is registered for the draft under the U.S.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Selective Service System, which is a list of individuals who can be conscripted into the armed forces in the event of a national emergency.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] When asked why he had not previously disclosed his dual citizenship, Scheer stated that he had never been asked about it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] It was seen as hypocritical since Scheer had attacked former Governor General Michaëlle Jean on this same issue and because the Conservatives had attacked Thomas Mulcair and Stéphane Dion on this issue.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer defended the former by stating that he was asking a question to his constituents and said that he was not leading the party at the time when it came to the latter situation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Over the next days, he refused to explain how he traveled to the United States without a valid U.S. passport.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] It is against the law for U.S. citizens to do so without a valid U.S. passport.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 11, the CBC filed an application in the Federal Court of Canada against the Conservative party over the use of television excerpts in partisan advertising.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] They claimed the party's use of excerpts violated the "moral rights" of news anchor Rosemary Barton and reporter John Paul Tasker.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The action was brought despite the material having been taken down from websites and deleted from Twitter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The CBC said that it was given no reassurance that such use would not be repeated.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The lawsuit says that the use of the material in a partisan way "diminishes the reputation" of the CBC and leaves it open to allegations that it is biased.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 14, Scheer ruled out any coalition or negotiations with the Bloc Québécois.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He said that he "does not need to work with the Bloc Québécois to deliver results for Quebec" and that he can work with Quebec Premier François Legault to deliver them.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 16, Scheer said that the party with most seats should have the right to form government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A day later, he stood by his claim and added that is what has happened in modern history.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Journalists pointed out that it was not the case and gave examples such as the 2018 New Brunswick general election and the 2017 British Columbia general election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 18 and 19, *The Globe and Mail* and CBC News revealed that the Conservative Party hired Warren Kinsella to "seek and destroy" the People's Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Bernier filed a complaint to Elections Canada over what he called "a secret campaign to smear his party".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Scheer did not say or deny that the Conservatives hired a consultant to destroy the PPC.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] NDP candidates were dropped or stepped down during the course of the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On June 20, Rana Zaman, candidate for Dartmouth—Cole Harbour, was dropped over comments about the Israeli–Palestinian conflict that the party deemed "unacceptable".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 16, Pierre Nantel, candidate for Longueuil—Saint-Hubert, was de-selected after reports surfaced of ongoing discussions regarding Nantel joining the Green Party of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 11, Dock Currie, candidate for Kamloops-Thompson-Cariboo, was forced to resign over "flippant and aggressive" comments he made toward pro-pipeline activists.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The next day, Olivier Mathieu, candidate for Lasalle-Emard-Verdun, stepped down following allegations of physical abuse against his ex-spouse.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] During the election, Jagmeet Singh has faced questions about wearing of a turban and whether that would reduce the number of people who would vote for him.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Jonathan Richardson, the former federal NDP's executive member for Atlantic Canada, who defected to the Green Party, stated in an interview with CBC Radio, that some potential NDP candidates were hesitant to run in New Brunswick, due to Singh's turban.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] CTV News covered a Singh event in Verner, Ontario and spoke to a number of voters there, including NDP supporters, who said that they would not vote for a leader wearing a turban.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] CBC News found a similar reaction in Ruth Ellen Brosseau's riding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He explained some things about his turban and recorded a French ad without it to alleviate people's worries.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Furthermore, according to Alexandre Boulerice, the party's Deputy Leader and Quebec lieutenant, the NDP is targeting young voters and they do not care about the turban.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 2, a man told Singh to cut off his turban to look more Canadian during a campaign stop.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Singh replied that Canadians "look like all sorts of people" before walking off.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] During the campaign, Singh talked about what he would do in a minority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 22, due to the controversy over Scheer's previous comments about same-sex marriage, he announced that the NDP would not support a Conservative minority government under any circumstances.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 22, Singh announced that despite Trudeau's past brownface and blackface incidents, he would not rule out working with the Liberals in a minority scenario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He later added that changing the way the country votes is also a condition (Singh's NDP backs a system of mixed-member proportional representation).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He added that he does not rule out supporting a pipeline-owning Liberal minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 13, Singh said he would "do whatever it takes" to keep the Tories from power, including forming a coalition government with the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He added that he is "ready to work with anyone", when he was asked about the Bloc.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The following day, Singh backed off those comments and urged Canadians to vote NDP in order to receive services like universal pharmacare and dental care.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, Singh said that coalition is not a dirty word and doubled down on his view that under no circumstance would his party support the Conservatives in a minority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 9, André Parizeau, Bloc candidate for Ahuntsic-Cartierville, created attention over his past communist affiliations as Leader of the Parti communiste du Québec (PCQ).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Parizeau disavowed the PCQ in order to be accepted as candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In October, the Bloc Québécois called on Quebeckers to vote for candidates "who resemble you" (" des gens qui nous ressemblent ") in the election, prompting NDP Leader Jagmeet Singh to denounce the message as unacceptable and divisive.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] During the English debate, Blanchet called the translation of his words dishonest and mentioned that the same words were used by Igniatieff in 2011 and Mulcair in 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 10, *Le Journal de Montréal* discovered that four BQ candidates had made anti-Islam and racist social media posts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A Bloc spokeswoman said it was up to Quebeckers to judge its candidates' social-media posts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The comments were condemned by Elizabeth May, Jagmeet Singh, Mélanie Joly and Françoise David.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, the candidates all posted the same apology on their respective social media accounts and Yves-François Blanchet apologized for his candidates' Islamophobic and racist social media posts.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 13, Blanchet announced that they will not support a coalition or a party in a minority scenario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Bloc will go issue by issue and support what is best for Quebec.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Several GPC candidates were dropped or stepped down during the course of the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On July 23, Brock Grills, Green candidate for Peterborough—Kawartha, stepped down for "personal reasons".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Grills was accused of fraud by a former employer but he and the EDA president stated that accusation was not the reason behind his stepping down.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Grills, who repeated his reasoning, also mentioned the Green Party central office "pushed" for his resignation because he was reaching out to other parties to ask them to adopt policies to curb climate change.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 16, Luc Saint-Hilaire, Green candidate for Lévis—Lotbinière, was forced to resign because of a Facebook post demanding Boufeldja Benabdallah, co-founder of the Centre Culturel Islamique de Québec, to denounce a man who allegedly lit his ex-wife on fire.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 12, Erik Schomann, Green candidate for Simcoe North, resigned over a 2007 Facebook post which appeared to suggest he wanted to mail pieces of a pig carcass to Muslims in support of the protesters during the Muhammed comic controversy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 7, Marthe Lépine, candidate in Glengarry—Prescott—Russell, was dropped over anti-abortion comments; however, as the party missed the deadline to remove her from the ballot, she remained despite being disavowed.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 9, the Green Party issued a statement insisting that there is "zero chance" of reopening the abortion debate; few hours after May stated the Green Party will not ban members from trying to reopen abortion debate in an interview.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] May later added that MPs risk being ousted if they move to reopen the debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] From September 10 to 16, attention was focused on Pierre Nantel, the candidate for Longueuil—Saint-Hubert.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He created this attention over his comments about Québec separatism on a Quebec radio station.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] May disputed that Nantel was a Quebec sovereigntist, but Nantel contradicted her afterwards.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] However, May stated he could be still be a candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Some journalists and columnists were confused by her reasoning for keeping him as a candidate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Furthermore, May was asked by the son of the late Jack Layton to not use the latter for political points when defending Nantel.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 10, Mark Vercouteren, the candidate for Chatham-Kent-Leamington, and Macarena Diab, the candidate for Louis-Hébert were revealed to have made "anti-abortion statements".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A spokesperson defended both of them but a few days later, it was revealed by May that Vercoutern was being "re-vetted" over the party not noticing Vercouteren's questionnaires.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A week after the original comments were revealed, Vercouteren stated his view aligned with the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 12, Dale Dewar, Green candidate for Regina—Qu'Appelle, apologized for making past negative comments on social media about Israel, Zionism and Israelis.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 15, the Green Party found anti-Islam social-media posts by four of its Quebec candidates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Starting on September 23, the GPC drew scrutiny around the world for manipulating a picture of Elizabeth May to make it seem as if she was using a reusable cup and metal straw instead of a disposable cup.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] When she was on *Tout le monde en parle*, May clarified that the original photo featured a compostable cup; the picture was modified to add the GPC's logo.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] She did admit that it was ridiculous that a staffer modified the picture.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Leading up to and during the campaign, May talked about what she would do in a minority.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 3, she announced that she would not be prepared to prop up any minority government of the major parties given current climate plans.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, on September 26, May announced that the GPC would not prop up a minority government that moves forward with the Trans Mountain pipeline expansion.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In the final week of the campaign, the idea of a coalition took hold.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] May said that in countries with proportional representation, parties can plan to govern together before the election, but that in Canada such talk is "meaningless" due to the first-past-the-post system.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] In February 2019, LaPresse discovered that Martin Masse, the PPC's spokesperson, had written controversial blog posts in the past.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] *The Star* discovered that four members of the PPC had used racist and anti-immigrant rhetoric.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] They were removed from the party as a result.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Bernier himself has been accused multiple times of using dog-whistle politics.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Bernier responded to this by saying racists are not welcome in his party and acknowledging that Canada is a diverse country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, Maxime Bernier generated a reaction after a photograph of him with members of an anti-immigration group surfaced online.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A few weeks later, he was also reprimanded for being photographed with Paul Fromm.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A spokesperson stated that Bernier had no idea who Fromm was, but once again experts were skeptical of the explanation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 23, news sites revealed that one of the PPC's founding members was a White nationalist and two others had ties to Anti-immigration groups.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] One of those founding members—a former American neo-Nazi leader—was volunteering for the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He was also a member of the Ontario Progressive Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He was removed from the party on August 29, after his past came to light.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The PPC's spokesperson said that it did not come up during the vetting process since he came from the US.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] They later cited to Global News that his removal was an example of the Party taking a stand against racism.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The party told *Le Devoir* that they did not have enough resources to vet them at the beginning of the PPC 's formation and the two other members denied having racist views.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On July 30, Cody Payant, People's candidate for Carlton Trail—Eagle Creek, attracted attention for a social media post defending Lindsay Shepherd.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Payant argue that it was taken out of context.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Bernier defended Payant after he spoke to Payant and was satisfied with his explanation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 2, Maxime Bernier called Greta Thunberg "mentally unstable" on Twitter.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] A few days later, he backtracked his comments stating his intention was to criticize her role as "a spokesperson for climate alarmism" and did not mean to denigrate her.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] After the campaign, Bernier classified these comments as his only election regret and as a mistake.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 18, Steven Fletcher, People's candidate for Charleswood—St.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] James—Assiniboia—Headingley, denied allegations for illegally using campaign signs and voter data from the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Fletcher also suggested that the move was political motivated from the Conservative and took issues to the fact that the letter was leaked online.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 19, 2019, Nancy Mercier, People's candidate for Beauséjour, raised concern from local organizations over comments about Islamism and immigration Mercier indicated her concerns are with Islamic terrorism and not members of any race.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 10, Sybil Hogg, the candidate for Sackville-Preston-Chezzetcook, came under fire for a series of anti-Islam tweets calling Islam "pure evil" and for the religion to be banned in Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The PPC's executive director reached out to her to understand the context and Hogg explained that she failed to draw the distinction between "Islam" and "Islamism" or "radical Islam".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] She added that her concern was radical Islam and not Islam.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Due to the response, the PPC said they would not take action against her.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Later, Bernier called the tweets "absolutely racist and Islamophobic" and confirmed that she will not face consequences.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Several candidates were dropped or stepped down before the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 6, Ken Pereira, People's candidate for Portneuf—Jacques-Cartier, stepped down because of a "terrible family tragedy".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] When announced as the candidate, Pereira had attracted attention for his online "anti-vaccine" and "pro-conspiracy theory" posts and was defended by the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 12, Brian Misera, People's candidate for Coquitlam—Port Coquitlam, claimed that he was removed for asking Bernier to denounce racism more clearly in an online video posted on Misera's Twitter account.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] However, the PPC stated that Misera was removed after he allegedly admitted to the party that he was his own financial agent, a violation of Elections Canada rules.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Yet a statement of Misera's disqualification obtained by City News made no reference to the PPC's claim or Misera's claim.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On September 30, Chad Hudson, People's Party candidate for the Nova Scotia riding of West Nova, tweeted that he would no longer be running for the party, less than two hours before Elections Canada's deadline for candidates to officially register to be on the ballot.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] He criticized the party and its leadership for being "divisive", as well as "bad for democracy" and contributors to the "toxic state of politics".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Hudson, later admitted that he did not notify the party of his decision.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 8, Victor Ong, the People's Party of Canada candidate in Winnipeg North, resigned after deciding the party is "racist and intolerant".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 19, environmental groups were warned by Elections Canada that any third party that promotes information about climate change during the election period with paid advertising could be engaging in partisan activity.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Registered charities with a charitable tax status would be required to register as a third party for the election if they engaged in any partisan activity incurring $500, which would include advertising and surveys, or risk their charitable tax status.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] After confusion about the warning, Elections Canada released a public statement to clarify that the prohibition applied only to advertising, not speech in general the following day.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On August 25, billboards purchased by a True North Strong & Free Advertising Corp., a third party promoting the People's Party of Canada's immigration policy, with the text "Say NO to Mass Immigration" appeared in Vancouver, Calgary, Regina, and Halifax.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] True North Strong & Free Advertising Corp is run by Frank Smeenk, the chief executive of a Toronto-based mining exploration company.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Peoples Party of Canada told the media that it had no contact with the group.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Initially, Pattison Outdoor Advertising defended the billboards, arguing that they complied with the Advertising Standards Canada Code but later decided to pull them and said that they would review their protocols on advocacy advertising.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Pattison president later revealed that the billboards would have stayed up had True North Strong & Free identified themselves on the billboards and how the public could get in touch with them.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] On October 3, the CBC revealed that the Manning Centre is a driving financial force behind a network of anti-Liberal Facebook pages pumping out political messaging and memes during the federal election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Facebook pulled one of their ads due to the excess violence.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] The Manning Centre's donations to those groups, worth more than $300,000, are hidden, since the think tank, which did not register as a third party, does not intend to disclose them.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] Elections Canada says there is nothing in the law to prevent outside groups from raising money and then passing those donations along to third-party advertisers.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] As a result of this lack of disclosure, Democracy Watch filed a complaint to Canada's Chief Electoral Officer.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p02] It argued that the Manning Centre should have registered as a third party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] During the Maclean's debate, Scheer said that refugees were "jumping the queue".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Journalists called this a false statement and one expert explained that "there is no queue".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On September 17, 2019, Brock Harrison, Scheer's director of communication, and the CPC tweeted that the RCMP had confirmed Trudeau was under investigation for SNC-Lavalin.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Scheer himself also repeated the allegation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Both tweets were removed after journalists deemed it to be false.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] A claim was circulating online that Bill Morneau was related to RCMP Commissioner Brenda Lucki through her husband, which is what was stopping the RCMP investigation regarding SNC-Lavalin.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The claim is false; Lucki's husband is not related to Morneau.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Furthermore, there has been no confirmation that there is an RCMP investigation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The *Buffalo Chronicle*, an American fake news website, promoted a false rumour about a sex scandal that supposedly resulted in Justin Trudeau's departure from West Point Grey Academy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The rumour was propagated by other fake news websites, gossip magazines, Warren Kinsella and Ezra Levant.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On October 7, 2019, the Conservatives issued a press release referencing the rumour and asking "why did Justin Trudeau leave West Point Grey Academy?".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The *Toronto Star* and *The Globe and Mail* devoted multiple reporters to the story and found nothing to corroborate it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The former headmaster also released a statement that said "there is no truth to any speculation that [Trudeau] was dismissed".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] During the campaign, the NDP claimed Bill Morneau had used tax-havens when he was the executive chair of Morneau Shepell, which was proven false.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] A probe by *Canadians for Tax Fairness* found that Morneau Shepell's subsidiary in the Bahamas was a legitimate business and not a way to avoid taxes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The NDP retracted the statement a few weeks after the campaign had ended.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] With 157, the Liberals won a plurality of seats in the House of Commons, allowing them to form a government albeit short of the majority government that they had won in 2015.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Liberals, under incumbent Prime Minister Justin Trudeau won the highest number of seats, at 157, allowing them to form a minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Conservatives under Andrew Scheer remained the Official Opposition and, with 121 seats, formed the largest opposition caucus in Canadian history.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Bloc Québécois won 32 seats under Yves-François Blanchet, the party's best result since 2008, and regained official party status after losing it in 2011, while the New Democratic Party under Jagmeet Singh was reduced to 24 seats, its worst results since 2004.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Greens saw its best result in the party's history, winning 3 seats, while independent MP Jody Wilson-Raybould was re-elected in the riding of Vancouver Granville and became the first independent to win a seat since 2008.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The newly created People's Party, meanwhile, lost its only seat, with party leader Maxime Bernier losing re-election in the riding of Beauce.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Aside from Bernier, every major party leader was able to secure election to the House of Commons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Marking the first time in Canadian history that no single party received more than 35% of the popular vote, the Conservatives won 34.41% of the popular vote, a plurality of the vote despite finishing 36 seats behind the Liberals, who won 33.07% of the vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Greens placed fifth with 6.55% of the popular vote, while the People's Party received 1.64% in its inaugural election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Liberal strength was predominantly concentrated in Eastern Canada and British Columbia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Ontario, the Liberals won 79 of the province's 121 seats, with a particularly strong showing in the Golden Horseshoe, where the party was not only able to fend off expected challenges from the Conservatives and the NDP but gain the Conservative-held ridings of Kitchener—Conestoga and Milton.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Atlantic Canada, the Liberals won 26 out of the region's 32 seats, sweeping Prince Edward Island and winning all but a single seat in both Newfoundland and Labrador and Nova Scotia.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Western Canada, the party won only 15 of the region's 104 seats, winning 11 seats in British Columbia and 4 in Manitoba and being shut out of Alberta and Saskatchewan for the first time since 2011 and 1988, respectively.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The best Liberal showing in Canada's west was in British Columbia, where they won 11 out of 42 seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Liberals also won two of the three territories, Yukon and the Northwest Territories.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Conservative strength was predominantly concentrated in Western Canada, particularly in Alberta and Saskatchewan, where the party won all but one of the 48 seats between the two provinces.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In British Columbia the Conservatives won 17 of the province's 42 seats, while in Manitoba the party won half the province's 14 seats, with the remainder split between the Liberals and NDP.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Conservatives increased their vote share in every district in three of those provinces (Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] However, it only resulted in a net gain of 10 seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Quebec, the second province where the Conservatives won a lower share of the popular vote than they did in 2015, the party won 10 of the province's 78 seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Atlantic Canada, the party was able to win 4 of the region's 32 seats after having been shut out entirely in 2015, winning 3 in New Brunswick and a single seat in Nova Scotia, though the party remained shut out of Newfoundland and Labrador and Prince Edward Island.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Only running in Quebec, the Bloc Québécois won 32 of the province's 78 seats, with the party doing particularly well in the Greater Montreal Area.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In Manitoba, the party won 3 of the province's 14 seats, picking up a single seat from the Liberals, while in each of Alberta, Quebec, Newfoundland and Labrador, and Nunavut the party won a single seat, gaining the latter riding for the first time since 1980.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Vote-splitting benefited the Conservatives in Ontario and Metro Vancouver, the Liberals in Quebec and the Maritimes, and the NDP in British Columbia and outside the GTA in Ontario.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] It also helped the Bloc in some Quebec ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Furthermore, analysis by different news outlets showed that the PPC cost the Tories six to seven seats.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] However, a Tory strategist said that it is not guaranteed that PPC voters would have voted for the Conservatives.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The PPC's spokesperson echoed similar sentiments.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Strategic voting was prominent across the country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] However, it was not the primary factor for most.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] According to a poll conducted after the election, of respondents who ultimately voted Liberal, 46 per cent said they had considered voting for the NDP at some point during the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Another 29 per cent considered voting Green.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Additionally, 15 per cent of Conservative voters considered voting for the People's Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Ninety-eight women were elected to federal seats in this election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] This also set a new record, both by number and by percentage, but still fell short of equality advocates' goal of 30% women.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The highest percentage of elected women was in the Green party, with two female MPs out of three elected Green Party members.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The 2019 CES included two survey components.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The non-probability online survey included a sample of Canadians from across the country (CPS n=37,822; PES n=10,337).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The goal was to gather enough data to allow for constituency-level analysis as well as proper subgroup analysis of populations that are typically underrepresented in the CES.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The RDD internet survey largely replicated the larger online study, although it contained fewer questions and has a smaller sample (CPS n=4,021; PES n=2,889).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In both surveys, the core questions were drawn from previous CES (to preserve continuity) on key issues such as vote intentions, issue positions, partisanship, and political engagement.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The 2019 Canadian Election Study was led by Laura Stephenson, Allison Harell, Daniel Rubenson and Peter Loewen.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The table below is the indicated vote choice in the 2019 election from the PES, cross-tabbed with demographic questions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Following the election, Trudeau ruled out a coalition and announced that his new cabinet would be sworn in on November 20, 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On November 4, 2019, Elizabeth May announced that she would be stepping down as leader of the Green Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On December 12, 2019, Andrew Scheer announced that he was resigning as leader of the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Defeated parties sought recounts in three ridings where the races were won by a few hundred votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Bloc Québécois made its request in the Quebec Superior Court for the ridings of Hochelaga and Québec and the NDP sought a recount for the riding of Port Moody—Coquitlam.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Federal judges accepted the requests and ruled that recounts should happen for those ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] All three recount requests were withdrawn during the recounting process, thus the victors stayed the same.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The nature of the elections' results reignited calls for electoral reform.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Some commentators argued against the current first-past-the-post system, while others defended it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Dominic O'Sullivan, Associate Professor of Political Science at Charles Sturt University, argued that Canada should follow in New Zealand's footsteps with their electoral reform.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] News outlets also published articles showing what the election results could have looked like if Trudeau had kept his promise on electoral reform.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] After the election, Elizabeth May sent Prime Minister Justin Trudeau a letter recommending STV as a compromise for electoral reform since it meets some of the concerns Trudeau expressed in the past.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] A poll published by the Angus Reid Institute showed that support for electoral reform and proportional representation in particular skyrocketed following the election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] After Justin Trudeau's re-election on October 21, 2019, #Wexit trended on social media.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] However, experts stated part of the push was due to disinformation and bots.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On November 4, 2019, the separatist group Wexit Alberta applied for federal political party status.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On November 6, 2019, a poll conducted by Ipsos show a historic high level of interest in secession from Canada in both Alberta and Saskatchewan by 33% and 27%, respectively.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] On January 12, 2020, Wexit Canada was granted eligibility for the next federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] They subsequently changed their name to the Maverick Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In late 2022, Global News reported on a suspected attempt by the government of China to infiltrate the Parliament of Canada by funding a network of candidates to run in the 2019 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Prime Minister Justin Trudeau stated on November 20, 2022, regarding alleged interference in the election that "I do not have any information, nor have I been briefed on any federal candidates receiving any money from China".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] In February 2023, the Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) concluded that the Chinese government interfered in the 2019 elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Progressive Canadian Party was deregistered by Elections Canada on October 30, 2019, for failing to comply with the reporting provisions of the Canada Elections Act.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The United Party of Canada was deregistered on December 31, 2020, for failing to submit required financial documents or update party information.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] The Stop Climate Change Party was deregistered on March 31, 2021, for failing to provide an auditor's report.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2019-canadian-federal-election-p03] Though there are 338 ridings in Canada, 341 were declared, as there were ties in three ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The **2021 Canadian federal election** was held on September 20, 2021, to elect members of the House of Commons to the 44th Canadian Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The writs of election were issued by Governor General Mary Simon on August 15, 2021, when Prime Minister Justin Trudeau requested the dissolution of parliament for a snap election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Trudeau won a third term as prime minister, his second minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Though the Liberals were hoping to win a majority government in order to govern alone, the results were mostly unchanged from the 2019 Canadian federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Liberals won the most seats at 160; as this fell short of the 170 seats needed for a majority in the House of Commons, they formed a minority government with support from other parties.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The 2021 election set a new record for the lowest vote share for a party that would go on to form a single-party minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The election was the second one in a row where the Liberals succeeded in winning a plurality of seats despite having fewer votes than the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Liberals won 32.6 per cent of the popular vote, while losing the popular vote to the Conservatives as they did in 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Conservatives led by Erin O'Toole won 119 seats, two fewer than their result in 2019, and continued as the Official Opposition.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois led by Yves-François Blanchet won 32 seats, unchanged from the prior election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The New Democratic Party led by Jagmeet Singh won 25 seats, a net increase of one seat, but nonetheless fell short of expectations.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Green Party maintained two seats but party leader Annamie Paul was defeated for the third time in her riding of Toronto Centre.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The party received 2.3 per cent of the popular vote, approximately a third of what they won in 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The People's Party did not win any seats, despite winning nearly 5 per cent of the popular vote, and party leader Maxime Bernier was defeated for the second time in his riding of Beauce.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Trudeau faced public blowback for holding an election in the middle of a global pandemic due to his expectation that doing so could translate his supposed rallying popularity into a landslide victory.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Criticism worsened when Trudeau failed to win by a majority and instead repeated his 2019 election showing.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] An official government probe later found that China attempted to meddle in the election to influence Canadian foreign policy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Paul resigned as Green Party leader two months after the election, and O'Toole was ousted as Conservative leader by his party's caucus in February 2022 over the poor showing in the election and other disagreements ongoing at the time.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In March 2022, the NDP and Liberals formed a confidence and supply agreement which lasted until the NDP withdrew in September 2024.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The 2019 Canadian federal election resulted in the Liberals, led by incumbent Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, losing both their parliamentary majority and the popular vote but nevertheless winning the most seats and remaining in office as a minority government.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Conservatives, who had gained seats and won the popular vote, continued as the Official Opposition.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québécois regained official party status and became the third party, replacing the New Democrats in that role, with the latter party losing seats but maintaining official party status as the fourth party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Although the Greens increased their seats in the House of Commons, they ultimately failed to achieve the required number of MPs (twelve) for official party status.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In the immediate aftermath of the 2019 federal election, all leaders initially announced that they would continue as the heads of their respective parties into the 43rd Canadian Parliament.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Elizabeth May said that she might not lead the Greens into the 44th federal election, and ultimately resigned as Green Party leader on November 4, 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On November 6, 2019, the members of the Conservative caucus decided not to adopt a measure which would have given them the ability to remove Andrew Scheer as leader; his leadership would still have been reviewed at the party's next convention, which was scheduled for April 2020.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On December 12, Scheer announced his intention to resign as leader.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] He stayed on until his successor Erin O'Toole was chosen and remains as the MP for Regina—Qu'Appelle.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On August 15, 2021, after a request from Prime Minister Trudeau, the Governor General dissolved parliament and called an election for September 20.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The table below lists parties represented and seats held in the House of Commons after the 2019 federal election, at dissolution, and after the 2021 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] An expected by-election in Haldimand—Norfolk to fill the vacant seat was rendered moot by the commencement of the general election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Below are the 31 MPs who chose not to run in the 2021 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The election call occurred at the same time as the fall of Kabul, on August 15.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Trudeau thus received criticism for not acting fast enough in the face of the 2021 Taliban offensive to evacuate Canadians from Afghanistan, as well as Afghans who supported Canada's military and diplomatic efforts during the War.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Criticism of Trudeau's decision to call an early election, particularly amidst the COVID-19 pandemic in Canada, was a major theme of his opponents' campaigns, and commentators noted a lack of support for a snap election amongst the public.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The beginning of the campaign proved difficult for the Liberals, who slightly fell behind the Conservatives in the polls of voting intentions.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Conservative released their platform on the second day of the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The party tried to change its image with this document by putting more focus on the environment, mental health, and LGBTQ+ rights issues.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Meanwhile, Trudeau attacked the new Conservative leader Erin O'Toole on the topics of compulsory vaccination for federal officials, abortion and the privatization of health care.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On August 25, Minister for Women and Gender Equality Maryam Monsef referred to the Taliban as "our brothers".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Many on social media shared the video of this statement, and saw this as an indication that she felt sympathetic to the terrorist group.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Monsef said that this was false, and further stated that she only chose those words because Muslims tend to refer to each other as "brothers".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On August 27, 2021, Trudeau was forced to cancel a campaign rally set for Bolton, Ontario, over security concerns arising from groups of protestors yelling obscenities at Trudeau.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] There were previous incidents of protesters showing up at his rallies criticizing COVID-19 vaccines and public health measures.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Foreign policy debates focused on China and the situation in Afghanistan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] For Afghanistan, discussions focused on ways to mitigate the immediate humanitarian crisis facing the country.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The group *Canadian Campaign for Afghan Peace* launched an open letter on August 17 calling on political parties to take position of the new situation in Afghanistan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The campaign took place during the extradition case of Meng Wanzhou, which had exacerbated tensions between Canada and China.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] O'Toole accused Trudeau of being "weak on China", and promised to scale up Canada's hostility towards the country if elected.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] According to Shadwick Martin, the tendency to relegate defence and foreign policy to minor appearances continued in 2021.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] He argues that the Liberals did not deviate from their government's existing foreign policy, while the Conservatives produced a lengthy list of reforms that one commentator described as "scattered and unfocused".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The NDP's propositions were essentially unchanged from 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] As in 2019, climate change was a major issue in the campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In March 2021, Conservative leader O'Toole announced a carbon pricing plan to replace the current Liberal carbon tax, despite previous Conservative opposition to any form of a carbon tax.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] There was thus a broad consensus among all represented parties for policies to mitigate climate change, although they differed in the emissions targets, the level of the carbon tax, and the transition path to a clean economy.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Only the People's Party opposed all climate change policies and vowed to withdraw from the Paris climate accord.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The COVID-19 pandemic was a major campaign issue.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Liberal party sought to defend its pandemic response, while trying to tie Erin O'Toole to Alberta Premier Jason Kenney.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] O'Toole always sidestepped questions about his previous support for Kenney's pandemic response by saying he would work with any premier to face the pandemic regardless of their political stripes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] During the campaign, Alberta was experiencing its worst wave of the pandemic in terms of hospitalisations.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Meanwhile, other parties explained what they would have done differently had they been in a similar situation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Bloc Québecois criticized the amount of money invested in Federal aid for workers, especially the Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The NDP, on the other hand, criticized the government's "aggressive" crackdown on possibly fraudulent CERB claims, while calling for clawing back wage subsidy payments to companies who fired their workers while received this benefit.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The People's Party was the only party opposing vaccine passports, mask mandates and lockdowns.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In September 2021, O'Toole changed his position on gun control.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Reverting from his initial promise of repealing Prime Minister Trudeau's May 2020 ban on assault weapons, he changed his stance on the issue, promising that he would not repeal the ban.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Political commentators and analysts described O'Toole's leadership as shifting the Conservative Party to the political centre.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Green Party of Canada experienced a period of infighting beginning in June 2021, when Jenica Atwin, one of its three MPs, crossed the floor to join the Liberal Party over a dispute regarding the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Although there were calls for the party leader Annamie Paul to resign, she stayed on as leader through the federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] She spent the majority of the election campaigning in her chosen riding of Toronto Centre, but failed to win the seat.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The campaign was also marked by a rise in support for the People's Party of Canada.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Before the election, Mainstreet Research gave the party more than 8 per cent of the vote, and Abacus Data noted particularly high scores among Canadians under the age of 60.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Justin Trudeau and Yves-François Blanchet indirectly accused the Conservatives for the rise of the PPC, with Trudeau notably criticizing Erin O'Toole for not requiring his party's candidates to be vaccinated.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Parliamentary Budget Officer provides a service to all parties for evaluating the financial impact of any of their proposals, but does not release details until the requesting party has done so as well.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] After the election, the PBO revealed that 130 requests had been received from all parties, of which only 72 were made public.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] It did release a report outlining various baselines that were used in its costing exercises.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In June 2020, the Leaders' Debates Commission released its report reviewing the 2019 election debates and making recommendations for future debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The report recommended a permanent and publicly funded commission be tasked with organizing two debates for every federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] It also called for the commission, not the government, to set the criteria for participation in future election debates.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The English-language debate gained notoriety when the moderator posed a question to Blanchet that characterized Quebec's law on secularism as "discriminatory".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] He challenged her use of that word, and the response was seen by some as a turning point in the Bloc's campaign, which gained in the polls after the debate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On August 29, Ici Radio-Canada Télé hosted a special broadcast consisting of a series of solo interviews with each leader in turn, with questions posed by Patrice Roy, Céline Galipeau and Anne-Marie Dussault.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] This format was not attempted by any of the other broadcasters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Liberals maintained their status as largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The results were very close to those of the 2019 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In a federal election, a judicial recount is automatically ordered in a riding where the margin of victory is less than 0.1 per cent (one one-thousandth) of the votes cast.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] While no validated results triggered an automatic recount in this election, judicial recounts were requested in four ridings: Brome—Missisquoi, Davenport, Châteauguay—Lacolle and Trois-Rivières.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Only Châteauguay—Lacolle saw its initial result overturned: the recount had Liberal incumbent MP Brenda Shanahan proclaimed the ultimate winner over Bloc candidate Patrick O'Hara, by a margin of only 12 votes.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] It was the first time validated results were reversed by a judicial recount since the 2008 election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Recounts in Brome—Missiquoi and Davenport began on October 12; however, in both ridings the early count appeared to confirm the initial validated results, leading both challengers to concede defeat and the recount to be terminated.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Initially, the preliminary results of Charleswood—St.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] James—Assiniboia—Headingley in the province of Manitoba were so close that the Liberal former MP Doug Eyolfson had just 24 votes fewer than the Conservative incumbent MP Marty Morantz, a margin small enough to trigger an automatic recount.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] On September 28, Eyolfson conceded after the validated results had widened the gap to 460 votes, which is approximately 1 per cent of the total vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Incumbents are denoted in bold and followed by *(I)*.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The remarkable similarity of the results and those of the 2019 federal election may have reinforced voters' sentiments that the early election was unnecessary, and its meagre results have left their mark on the electorate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] A survey by Maru Public Opinion revealed that 77 per cent of respondents believe that Canada is more divided than ever, and 52 per cent feel that Canada's democratic system is broken.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Several factors were quickly identified as having had a significant influence on the results.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Some political scientists and commentators debated whether the PPC's better performance, compared to the 2019 federal election, contributed to the Conservatives under Erin O'Toole losing to the Liberals.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Mainstreet Research CEO Quito Maggi and University of Toronto political science professor Nelson Wiseman posited that the PPC may have cost the Conservatives at least ten ridings.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The votes obtained by PPC candidates were larger than the margin of victory in 21 ridings, where the Conservative candidate was in second place (12 in Ontario, five in BC, two in Alberta, one in Quebec and one in Newfoundland).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Of those seats, 14 went to the Liberals, six to the NDP, and one to the Bloc; however, it has been described as not a simple generalization, as a significant amount of PPC support arose from non-Conservative voters.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Important vote swings to the Liberals were also noted in ridings with significant Chinese-Canadian populations, with especially large ones arising in Aurora—Oak Ridges—Richmond Hill and Richmond Centre.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Even before the mail-in ballots were counted, the Liberals were projected as leading in 158 seats despite seeing their vote share fall from 33.1 per cent to 32.3 per cent.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Gerald Butts, former principal secretary to Trudeau, praised the result as a "smart campaign" that prioritized "vote efficiency"; this view was criticized as detracting from other essential aspects of an election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Other commentators questioned whether the Liberal vote has reached its effective limit, commenting that minority governments have occurred with greater frequency since the Unite the Right movement and the formation of the Conservative Party in 2003.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Had he not been ousted by his caucus, O'Toole would have faced a mandatory leadership review at the next Conservative national conference in 2023.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] A member of the national council quickly called for a petition to accelerate the process.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Other Conservatives urged continued support of O'Toole, and called for the party to unify around him.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Most party and caucus members seemed to have appeared to favour a *post-mortem* review along the lines conducted by the party after the 2004 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Green Party saw its share of the vote collapse to 2.3 per cent, its lowest level since the 2000 federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Internal dissension and poor morale contributed to the decline, and Elizabeth May called for an inquiry to determine the underlying reasons for it.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Paul announced her resignation as party leader on September 27.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Commentators at *The Conversation* noted that for a second election in a row the Liberals won the greatest number of seats but lost the popular vote to the Conservatives under the first-past-the-post (FPTP) voting system.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] During the campaign, Trudeau said he remains open to getting rid of Canada's FPTP if re-elected, provided there is consensus on the issue; he also expressed his preference for ranked voting over proportional representation.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Trudeau had promised during the 2015 campaign that the 2015 federal election would be the last federal election to use FPTP.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In the lead-up to the 2021 federal election, western alienation was seen as a potentially disruptive force, particularly in Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Wexit Party, led by former Conservative MP Jay Hill, positioned itself as a western separatist alternative to the federal Conservatives, drawing comparisons to the Bloc Québécois.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The party changed its name to the Maverick Party in September 2020.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Support for western separatism rose during 2020, with polling showing as much as 45–48% support for independence in Alberta.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] However, media attention toward the movement and the party declined after the rebranding.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] There was inconsistency about whether to treat the Maverick Party as a major party, with some outlets—such as 338Canada— including it in regional projections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Caught off guard by the early election call, the party managed to nominate only 29 candidates, primarily in Conservative strongholds in Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Though they had also nominated a few in British Columbia and Manitoba.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Some analysts suggested that the People's Party of Canada attracted part of the Maverick Party's potential voter base.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Maverick Party ultimately received just 0.21% of the national popular vote.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] However, in the ridings where it fielded candidates, it received approximately 2.3% of the vote and outperformed the Green Party in Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] After the election, western separatist sentiment appeared to wane.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Some Maverick Party members were involved in the 2022 "Freedom Convoy" protests.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The party's public activity declined afterward, and it formally dissolved in early 2025, citing lack of electoral success and organizational challenges.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Forty-nine MPs were elected for the first time, and two more (Randy Boissonnault and John Aldag) returned after having been defeated in 2019.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The number of female MPs—103, up from 100 in 2019—is a record high for the House, and 22 of the first-time MPs are women.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Kevin Vuong, whose candidacy was disavowed by the Liberals after nominations had closed, still won the riding of Spadina—Fort York.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Vuong announced that he would take his seat as an independent upon being sworn in.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Adam Vaughan, the previous incumbent, called on Vuong to resign as his victory was "compromised".
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In a radio interview in November, Vuong apologized to his supporters, and he later said, "Of the many, many people who have reached out since my interview, they've encouraged me to move forward.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] George Chahal, elected in Calgary Skyview, was the subject of several complaints concerning the removal of campaign flyers of another candidate, substituting them with his own.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In January 2022, he accepted and paid a $500 administrative monetary penalty assessed by the Commissioner of Canada Elections in the matter, saying, "It's just a late night on an election campaign.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Call it a dumb mistake or brain fog—it really doesn't matter why I did what I did.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] A year following the election, Conservative Party politicians including former leader Erin O'Toole blamed Chinese government interference as a factor behind the loss for the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Similar views were shared by O'Toole's director of parliamentary affairs Mitch Heimpel who claimed Canadian national security officers had contacted the Conservatives around election day to express concerns about potential foreign interference.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The Procedure and House Affairs Committee of the House of Commons met to discuss these reports, and voted to expand their current inquiry into the 2019 election to include the 2021 election as well.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] In April 2024, an inquiry into foreign interference heard that CSIS concluded in February 2023 that the Chinese government interfered in the 2019 and 2021 elections.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The 2021 Canadian Election Study (CES) comprised two phases: a Campaign Period Survey (CPS) and a Post-Election Survey (PES).
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The CPS involved three components—“CPS,” “CPS Modules,” and “CPS Oversample”—which were consolidated into a final dataset of 20,968 respondents.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Data collection for the CPS was conducted between August 17 and September 19, 2021.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The PES followed shortly after, occurring from September 23 to October 4, 2021, and yielded a sample size of 15,069.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The survey's core questions were adapted from prior iterations of the CES to maintain consistency and focus on key topics, including voting intentions, demographics, issue positions, partisanship, and political engagement.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The 2021 CES was directed by a team of researchers: Laura Stephenson, Allison Harell, Daniel Rubenson, and Peter Loewen.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The data presented include questions from the CPS and PES, cross-tabulated with 2021 voting preferences.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] The weights applied to the data were adjusted to align with the actual results of the 2021 Canadian federal election.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/2021-canadian-federal-election] Both Lanark—Frontenac—Kingston and Ville-Marie—Le Sud-Ouest—Île-des-Sœurs are tied, resulting in only 336 of 338 ridings being declared.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] The **Animal Protection Party of Canada** (French: *Parti pour la protection des animaux du Canada*) is a federal political party in Canada that focuses on animal rights and environmentalism.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] It was formed in 2005 as the **Animal Alliance Environment Voters Party of Canada** by the merger of two organizations, the Animal Alliance of Canada and Environment Voters; it changed to its current name in 2016.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] Both parent organizations have been vocal in opposition to the seal hunt in Newfoundland and Labrador, fur farming, trapping, and bear hunting.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] The party is led by Liz White, a Toronto-based animal rights advocate.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] Federal laws restricting political advocacy by "third parties" (i.e., organizations not registered by Elections Canada as political parties) during election campaigns led to the formation of this party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] Following a Supreme Court of Canada ruling that allowed political parties to be registered by only running a single candidate, animal rights activists formed the party.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] The AAEV party provides its members and candidates the opportunity to promote its views during election periods.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] The party originally endorsed major-party candidates who promoted positions favourable to its own.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] In the 2006 general election, AAEV's free-time political ads endorsed the New Democratic Party, counterbalanced by the statement that voters could also vote for AAEV party leader Liz White in Toronto Centre.
[src:animal-protection-party-of-canada/animal-protection-party-of-canada] Canadian electoral laws hinder misuse of this loophole by setting campaign spending limits for parties, proportional to the number of voters in the electoral districts where the party is running candidates.
